title: I've been wearing this watch for 15 years
text:
Granted, not the same watch, I've replaced it multiple times over the last 15 years. But with a watch this cheap I don't feel bad doing it. This look is CLASSIC, straight 80's classic and a timeless design still feels of this moment whenever that happens to be.

I work as a carpenter so I chew through watches quickly since my hands and wrists are always getting battered around. That being said, they stand up to direct hammer blows and smashing into sheets of plywood or scratching along lengths of steel without any issue. I treat these watches terribly and they keep on telling time perfectly, the backlight never fails nor the alarm.

What always fails before the watch does is the band, usually after 1-2 years of daily abuse and taking it on/off to shower the watch band with tear. That or the crystal will become so scratched from accidents that it's time to buy a new one. But who cares! These watches are so affordable I don't mind trading an old, tired one for a brand new one.

I love these watches. They look great, they do their job and they're wicked tough. I'm sure I'll continue wearing these for another 15 years to come.

This wrist watch is also what President Barack Obama was wearing while he was in the White House for 8 years. It's timeless design and the simplicity you just can't beat. A Highly recommended wrist watch.

title: Great Watch - Accurate - Fairly Rugged - The Strap Is Very Short, Though
text: I've had a few F91W series watches, and they've all been reliable.  They're so inexpensive, and run so long on the original batteries, they're pretty much disposable.  Over the years, I've bought several of these watches - not to wear on my wrist, but to strap them to my backpack, mount on my bike, and keep in my camp packs.  These are excellent and accurate timepieces to have around, to quickly tell time when your hands are occupied.  Just to try it out, however, I put a new F91W-1 watch on my wrist...  Or, rather, I ~tried~ to put it onto my wrist, but it didn't fit.  I'm not Lou Ferigno or The Big Show, and I could barely touch the tip of the strap to the very tip of the buckle.  I compared it to my older F91W, and it too had a small strap.  A no-name watch from Hong Kong with another "standard men's strap" was a good centimeter longer.  It's not a problem for me, since I don't plan on wearing it, but it's something to keep in mind when purchasing this watch.  As a timepiece, the F91W-1 still great.  Accurate, rugged, water resistant, inexpensive and very plain looking.  I'll trust my life to it as a timepiece, but apparently I won't be wearing them unless I buy a new strap.

title: Good Standard Watch
text:
These are good little watches and I have been using them since they came out 20-30 years ago. I am not sure if the model number has changed but the simple basic Casio digital watch has always been long lasting and dependable. They are not expensive but have served me well. If it gets broken while working or playing I don't worry and I never have to be concerned that someone will rob me for my watch while traveling to other countries.

But from a display standpoint it could be better. Although the display is common with all of these style watches, the illumination button is useless. It does not produce enough light or at the correct angle to read the numbers. I since have started using the Casio F-105 Illuminator, same basic watch but with an outstanding back light feature.

So if you are looking for a good basic watch with typical features such as 24hr time, alarm, stop watch and large clear digital numbers then this is a good choice. But, if you want to see what time it is at night or in poor lighting then get the F-105.

title: Good old standby
text:
When it comes to technology, I am a utilitarian. In other words, I don't want to spend money on a bunch of features that I don't really need. I remember wearing a watch just like this as a kid during the 1980s, and it served its purpose just fine. It also lasted a long, long time. So when I needed a cheap watch to wear while exercising, I decided to buy the same kind that worked for me all those years ago.

What you get here is a durable and tough watch that will tell you what time it is and beep when it's time to wake up. It'll also work underwater. That's about all it does. If this set of features is what you want, this watch is probably the absolute best value available.

If you like no-frills, plain-and-simple-tried-and-true products, sporting a watch like this is a good way to show it!

title: Great for US Military
text:
I purchased this watch because I've been eyeing this (and it's metal/chrome counterpart) for years now. This is all of the information I needed on a smartwatch screen. After my last apple watch bit the dust, I decided to go for an old-fashioned wristwatch. I am also joining the US Navy and needed a black wristwatch with an alarm - they sell them at basic, but I want to already be familiar with my watch beforehand. This fit the bill perfectly.

For $10, this thing is amazing. Setting it is a breeze. You program the month into the watch so it knows how many days there are, so you don't have to reset it monthly like many mechanical watches that show the date. So you literally just set everything once and you're set.

I love how light it is - I'll probably end up sleeping with this thing on. I am a tall guy and the face is a bit small, however the information is clearly present and easy to see.

My only complaint is the light. It lights up the left side of the screen, but the 1/3 in the middle and 1/3 to the right are still pretty dark. I can use the light and see the info okay in the dark, so it does serve its purpose. It could be better though, but this is where I'm like "I paid $10 for this thing", so over all not an issue.

DEFINITELY recommended. May not be pretty, but I've always been a "function over fashion" sort of person, and this watch is amazing.

Highly recommend, especially if you need something for military service.

text:
This is not the only watch I have bought over the last 30 years but it is the only watch I should have bought over the last 30 years.

I try to keep at least 2 back up F91W watches waiting in the wings as they are not indestructible and the things I do test them to the max.

Easy to set and use and you cannot beat the price. When the strap breaks and all straps will break, the watch becomes a glue on time piece.

My lawn mower has one I use to measure elapsed time as it takes 6 hours to mow my lawn and I spread it out over 12 days. My DR brush cutter 300 plus pound mower is not hill friendly and consumes a lot of energy. This watch silicon cemented to the console beside the factory rpm and lube time meter tells me when to head for the barn.

I see no reason to buy any other timepiece.

title: too few features, some flaws
text:
I am very disappointed in this watch, the F-91W.

I have owned a different watch, the Casio W-71 for many years, and find it to be a versatile watch, but the band just broke (as they do after several years). I purchased the F-91W awhile back as a future replacement, but found it lacking seriously when I had to use it. I would have sent it back, but considering the cost of shipping, it was not worth it.

The features are scaled back compared to the W-71. There is no count-down timer, which I use almost daily. The button that cycles through the features goes through the "change time," making it easy to change the time by mistake. (The button layout is not convenient for someone who uses the different features multiple times daily, but I concede that may be my bias.) I also use the feature to set an alarm for a specific date (the one day I have to catch a plane at 6 am), so I do not forget and get awakened at 4 am for the next few days. There are more limitations and flaws in addition to these I have listed.

Pros:
cheap
its a Casio

Cons:
too easy to change the time by mistake
limted features
no month on date, just the day (fine, my pet peeve)
no count down timer
single alarm mode
(button layout not as easy to use)

The W-71 is about twice the cost, but well worth it. I am going to find a replacement band (or two) for my old one, and put this F-91W back in a drawer.

Spend the extra $10 for a much better watch. Stock up on replacement bands at Wal-Mart or such and it will last for many years.

title: Solid watch!
text:
Dotted throughout the sea of reviews, I saw that folks thought this watch was too small. BUT. I can kinda see that if you are on the heavier or just bulkier side. If you're even relatively slender this watch fits wonderfully. The backlight works in the situation where it counts; bleary eyed at who-knows-when o'clock. BUT YOU KNOWS WHEN. Because the screen is lit up just enough to read the time! I have this watch worn with the face on the palm-side of my wrist. My leather cuff fits over it so i can read the time between the fasteners.

I love this watch and if it only last 6 months to a year I'll be happy with the $10 spent.

EDIT/UPDATE: August 5th, 2017! Still going well! And in fact, I've made friends with other folks wearing the same watch! We end up talking about how awesome digital watches and alarm clocks are.. Because we're boring I s'pose. BUT. Still going strong. Its 30sec alarm beeps wakes me more often than my phone's alarm. 10/10 would recommend still

title: Cheap and functional, especially for sports.
text: You can't ask for much more in a sports watch.  It's a basic alarm chronograph with an auto calendar.  But unlike other sports watches, it isn't bulky.  The G-shocks and stuff are great watches, but they hang up on your gear and get in your way.  This is small, inexpensive, and seems to be indifferent to anything I do to it.

title: Worthless light
text: I had another cheap Casio that I really liked. After a year or two the strap buckle broke, so I got this one...not the same. It's not as comfortable for some reason and the light is horrible. I am very, very disappointed with this light.

title: Great watch- I've been using these for years
text: I've been using these watches for many years (perhaps 20).  They do wear out eventually (perhaps after 8 or so years) but they are so cheap and function so well it is totally worth it. Also the straps are generally easy to replace.  I think my current one may run just a little fast, but not enough to be a big issue. I think I adjust it once every few months and it's only off by perhaps 2 minutes then.  I think the review above was probably written in 2016 when I purchased a new one. It's now August of 2019. The strap on that watch just broke and I was not able to find a replacement strap on Amazon so I went ahead and purchased  a new watch. Pity to throw out the old watch as it was still working fine but at $11 it didn't seem worth my while to search for a replacement watch band.  Bottom line- it is still a great watch!

title: Good value
text:
I had the older version of this watch when I was in the Army, it was a great and reliable companion to me, but I'm a bit disappointed that the quality has gone somewhat down in this product.

First, don't get me wrong, I love this watch; it has all of the features I want / need and it is stupid simple to program and switch between what you want to do.

However, the light on this watch has gone down significantly in quality from the older model. The older model had a great blue backup light that illuminated the whole display crisply and brightly. The one on this model is subpar at best; it illuminates from the side and casts a tiny bit of light across the screen. So only the first number is well lit, and you have to look very closely and very hard in order to see / guess what the other numbers are.

This watch could have gotten 5 stars if not for the crappy illuminator. But it's still a dang good buy for the money.

title: A true masterpiece of the human race.
text:
This watch is quietly badass. I'm being completely serious. When I see a dude with a giant timepiece, I think maybe he's compensating for something else or is just desperate for attention.

Wearing a small, minimal watch like this is a show of self-confidence.

And it's not bad-looking at all! A little dorky, but handsome. Now that most people no longer wear watches, I think wearing pretty much any watch at all adds a touch of style.

The strap may be too small for larger male wrists. While they're not really designed for it, you can put a 18mm NATO strap on one of these with a little effort. Check Y-Tube for details. It is possible to put a thin leather strap on there (I did) but the nylon ones are much easier.

text: This is a great little watch if you need something affordable and dependable fir doing dirty jobs like working on the car or going to the gym. Its light weight and easy to clean. And if you abuse it to the point of failure it's cheap to replace. I have an 8-1/4in wrist though. So the strap barely fit my wrist on the last hole. I have it to my son and he wears it when out playing football or basketball with his friends. It took some major punishment but it runs like a champ. If you have a larger worst and want a similar product, I went with the classic DW56OO Casio shock. At around $40 it's double the price but still super cheap for a watch. The stop watch chronograph functions are better and it's a g shock do its pretty much bullet proof and both watches have similar look and functions ...you can't go wrong either way. If you have a smaller wrist 6-7inches then the 91W is a fantastic bargain.

title: At a net cost of a quarter a month, this is the best deal going....
text:
Have had several of these over the years and will probably die with one on my wrist. Cheap, durable, easy for my seven decade old eyes to see. I'll keep until the battery dies or the strap snaps, then replace the whole thing since it's so cheap. Just had the battery on a Wal-Mart analog watch die on me and the last two years of squinting at the tiny date-day window and jacking it around after every thirty day month was too much. So Casio F91W-1 Classic, I'm glad to be back with you.

(Comments based on other reviews)-- There are comments about this being a child's watch. It is small, but I weigh 220 and am 6'3 and strap is in sixth hole in, so you'd have to have pretty big wrists before this wouldn't fit. The light is pretty dim, but I don't find that enough of a shortcoming to downgrade rating. I'm usually in my car when it's dark, have access to a clock or can dig out my phone--the watch is readable but not easy to see right portion of display.

title: Small, Mighty, and Cheap!
text:
This watch was perfect! I'm kind of in love.

I use an Apple Watch for my day to day, but this little watch actually gets used a lot. It is absolutely perfect for any outdoor activity or other situation when you need a seriously tough little watch. Its also a perfect travel companion.

According to Casio, this thing is only supposed to be water resistant, and isn't really meant for swimming. Well aren't they a bunch of jokers! I have swam for hundreds of hours with this watch on. In pools, rivers, lakes, oceans, and believe it or not, THE DEAD SEA!!! I am truly flabbergasted by the quality for how cheap it is. I honestly expected to break this watch over a dozen times by now, in fact I never bought it to last, it was really only meant for one trip.

Just so there are no surprises, the materials are what you would expect for a watch this cheap. Its all plastic hardware, and a simple thin resin strap, but somehow it has all held up. It still feels cheap in your hand at first, but after a while wearing it, you will realize how tough it really is.

title: Terrific for the price
text:
I use this watch because I don't like wearing bulky watches on my wrist. This watch is slim and steamlined and because it only has the basic features, it's cheap. I don't know how Casio can make any money on these.

The amazing thing is how durable they are. I've been wearing the same watch for almost five years now with no issues, except the plastic strap is starting to break. Best thing yet: the entire watch is so cheap, a replacement watch band costs almost the same price (around $10), so I just ordered another watch and will kept the current one as a spare in my backpack, for when I forget my watch at home!

So far I have not even had to replace the battery on mine. You can also get this watch at any Longs Drugs store for around the same price, if they are available in your area. With the free Supesaver shipping from Amazon, cost is the same.

This watch is perfect for day to day use, where you might scuff or damage whatever timepiece were on your wrist. If you play sports, go hiking, or work outside, this watch is great for you. title: Only reason we replace is due to a broken band, great quality for the price!
text:
These watches are great for the price. My husband has had 3 (well technically 4, but read below) over the last 8 years, and the only reason we replace is due to the band breaking. As I read on comments here, when the band breaks, for essentially the price of replacing the band, just buy a whole new watch, so that is what we do! There is no problem with the actual functions of the watch though. My hubby wears it all the time, during labor intensive jobs to swimming. Besides a turtle stealing it while scuba diving (the day after we purchased the first one it mysteriously disappeared while scuba diving), we haven't had a problem with one yet. We purchased a new one the next day and he did wear it scuba diving. He did not get mugged again it held up nicely. My husband does think the light on this one I bought off here is a touch more dim than usual though.
We love that we do not have to worry about breaking, losing, or being mugged by sea life because of low cost of these watches, but the quality far exceeds the price and they will forever be my husbands first choice in watches.

title: Casio F91W-1 Classic vs. Casio F105W-1A Illuminator
text:
Casio doesn't supply the information anywhere, but I'm quite certain that the only difference between this F91W-1 "Classic" watch and the F105W-1A "Illuminator" watch is the backlight. The F91W-1 uses a single LED for its lighting source, which is pretty weak. Note some of the complaints in these comments about the poor backlight quality. On the other hand, the F105W-1A uses an electroluminescent backlight, which is a far better uniform, bright backlight. It's blue, too. Hence its name of "Illuminator." Other than that, the two watches (and their bands) are identical. It's like comparing a lightbulb (Classic) to a glowing wall (Illuminator). BTW: both watches use an 18mm band.

So if the quality of the backlight is of concern to you, pop for the extra $3 and buy the Illuminator instead of the Classic. I've owned each model and gave up on the Classic because I didn't like the quality of its backlighting.

title: All function with just enough form to have become an enduring, timeless classic timepiece
text:
For the right kind of person, with just exactly the right sort of style (or appropriate lack thereof), the Casio F91W is every bit as good as, if not better than, a Cartier. Th F91W is a classic. It's remained virtually unchanged for decades, and there's a reason for that. Certainly, it has its own look. It's slim, sleek, and sports the cleanest of clean lines. It's simple, and it doesn't make a big fuss. It's comfortable, it's accurate, and it does enough. Its alarm is positively reliable, and its stopwatch is simple and consistent. It's small and unassuming, and doesn't draw a lot of attention to itself because it doesn't need to. This watch exists for its wearer and no one else. It doesn't try to impress, but it will never let you down. It does a few things and it does them well, all the while, not pretending to care at all about the things it doesn't do.

It's a perfect watch for a woman or a man, for a child or an adult. It's good for sport, and it's good for relaxing, and it's good for work, and it's just fine for everything else in between.

If this watch were a person, when asked the time, it would reply "quarter to three!" with a big grin on its face, and go back to its drink without missing a beat. It wouldn't huff and fumble for the time and act as if you were intruding on it before somehow giving you a time that was an hour too fast or slow.

But you knew that already, didn't you? It used to be that you could find an F91W accidentally, just out shopping in the department stores. And maybe you'd need a new watch so you'd pick one up. But today, and especially online, the F91W doesn't really find you as much as you go looking for it. You wouldn't be looking at it if you didn't already know it was perfect for you. And if it's not the watch for you, that's fine too, just move along to something else. The F91W isn't bothered. It knows who its people are.

text: My first purchase of this time piece iwas wonderful . This was my second watch as I broke the 1st one. I didn't care for the strap that came with it and bought a velco strap (Amazon.com - Voguestrap TX51012BK Allstrap 16-20mm Black Adjustable-Length Perforated Nylon Sport Strap Watchband) to replace the strap with the buckle. I had an awful time trying to take the stiff posts off the time piece, as it wouldn't slide out and did not have the spring collapsible post that is much easier to remove and install. It was extremely difficult to push or slide the posts out of the holes. As a result I had to bend the post to get it off. After finally getting it off the time piece, I straightened the post and struggled to install my preferred watch band. To add insult to injury, the light did not cover the entire time piece and I could see only the hour numbers and not minute numbers in the dark. I could have returned to have it replaced, but didn't feel like going through the aggravation of contacting Amazon to arrange an exchange and I certainly didn't want to go through the hassle  again of transferring the preferred watch band to the replaced time piece.

title: Perfect minimalist watch
text: I own about a dozen Casio digital watches (I'm kind of a collector) and this one is tied with my G-Shock DW-5600E as being my favorite.  Casio makes and sells tons of F-91 watches for a reason, and have done so for a long time. The beauty of this watch is that it is so light and thin that it almost becomes a part of your body and you forget that it is on your wrist. At the same time the F-91 is quite accurate, reliable, and sturdy considering it's super low cost. Even if it does break, which would require significant abuse, the low price means getting a new one is painless. The batteries on these things will last a good long time. As far as accuracy, my F-91 actually does much better than my DW-5600E. The style isn't for everyone but I personally love the retro look. The only down side is that you don't want to be caught in a warzone wearing one because ownership of an F-91 could get you accused of being a terrorist bomber and sent to Gitmo. That aside, for anyone who wants an inexpensive and / or retro style watch the F-91 is the clear choice.

title: CASIO Watch, This one's a real GEM
text:
I had this model watch back in the 70's... It was very reliable and never gave me a problem, I never gave it a thought. I recall a model I bought by Casio with the outside temperature indicator. Now a discontinued model, if you have that model in your dresser drawer, it is now worth over $250, without the wrist band.

IN THE BOX
You get a well packaged watch on a holder for shipping and instructions. Put these instructions in a place that you won't lose them. It seems everything comes with some sort of instruction and most the time, they are lost or thrown away. You may need these instructions sometime in the future.
BATTERY LIFE
The battery life is well over a year, depends on how much you use the dial light which is incandescent.

FUNCTIONS
Time, Alarm, StopWatch, Date, Hourly Chime

MY THOUGHTS
This model was great and where some watches had a problem with the wrist band cracking, I don't recall a big problem with the wrist band.
... I like having the hourly chime set. The hourly announcement is loud enough to hear in a quiet room but won't interfere with any meetings.
... This watch was introduced in the 70's and was a hit. It was a reasonably priced watch in a world of what I considered overpriced watches.
... Today, the store where I bought it has closed.

MY RECOMMENDATION
I whole heartedly recommend this Casio watch if you wanting a reliable watch with the hourly chime, alarm, a stopwatch and time with date function. Be aware the dial light is not LED so it uses quite a bit of the battery each time you use it. This has proven to be a very reliable watch and lasts for years, even after battery changes. Well worth the cost.

text: This isn't a watch you'd necessarily want to wear to the office or a black-tie function, but it'll do for everything else. It's lightweight, the timer and alarm functions are easy to navigate and it's water resistant. I was looking for something to keep around when doing yard work or just lounging around the house. I have a couple other watches that give off the "look how serious I am about keeping time" look, but when you're at home, you don't want some brick weighing your arm down constantly. So, I got this. A little rebellious purchase that tells corporate America, "Not in my house". Overall, a great purchase. I hope the battery last a long time. If not, I'll be back to comment on it; although, given the other reviews, I feel pretty good about my chances.

title: Still running after 7 Years!
text:
So I bought this watch in 2013. It is now year 2020. I got the watch to put on my motorcycle and bicycle because I wanted something that could tell time while I was riding. Plus if someone happened to steal it off my bike, I wouldn't be too butt hurt about it because it was only around $10. Well I left to on my mountain bike and pretty much forgot about it until recently when I went for a bike ride. The watch was kind of hidden around my handlebar bag wrapped around my my handlebar. I flipped the watch over and it was still running! I've never changed out the battery. The time was off by a few minutes but, it's been running for 7 years! Yah it feels cheap, it looks cheap, but I like it.

I saw pictures other people have posted with different bands to give it a unique, personal look. I might do the same. This is a great watch. I think Casio's are my favorite. Cheap and reliable. I might get me another one.

title: Okay for price but a few nits
text:
I had a similar Casio for decades - almost identical in appearance but with four buttons. This version is okay but not a good as the older version in the following respects:
1) There is no month displayed. Day of week and day of month, but not the month itself, despite there being room on the display. The month has to be set, but is not displayed. Disappointing.
2) The older version had the button to enter settings mode recessed, so it required a deliberate action to enter the settings. The button on this version is not recessed, so it is way too easy to accidentally enter the settings mode and change something unintentionally.
3) The wrist band does not appear to be removable, despite the appearance of pins at the joint. I was hoping to replace the band with my older flex band, but could not get the existing one off. The band on this version is not bad, just not as convenient for me as the flex band I had.

title: The Watch is very reliable, accurate and economical.  I use the features.
text: I have been buying this watch for 25 - 30 years.  They tend to last about 5 years until the strap breaks.  I use the stop watch feature several times a day and the date feature.  The alarms are also nice to have but I don't use them as much.  The light feature doesn't enable me to read the time int he dark.  This watch is so inexpensive that I usually buy 2 or 3 at a time in case a strap breaks or to keep one on standard time and the other on daylight savings time.  When the strap breaks I use them in the kitchen to time items which are being cooked.  The watch is very lightweight and I am not even aware that I am wearing it unless I specifically look at it.  I have never seen any watch that is so inexpensive yet has such a range of easy to use features.  If you want something to measure time and aren't concerned about having a prestige watch, this is the one for you as it is for me.  Joe Canino

title: Basic watch, small & light -- but with a pitiful light!
text:
The last couple of these I've bought (I've been wearing Casio watches for many years) were the larger, bulkier "Sport" models, which have larger, easier to read screen, and a few more features -- but much bulkier, and the straps were always oversize for my small wrists. Maybe that's one reason the bands never last long? But my guess is, poor Chinese plastic & quality control. My last two watches still work, and keep perfect time -- but it's a real pain to change the band. So when it broke, I thought, hell with it. For ten bucks... These would likely fit women too, who prefer this style of watch.

It is absurd to have to toss a perfectly good watch (w/ a 10-yr battery!) in the drawer, b/c the new band costs as much as a new watch! It is also annoying that each different Casio module has a different time-set sequence. This one is even LESS intuitive than the last. Bah. I just attempted to link instructions on how to turn off the annoying hourly "beep" -- since the instructions Casio supplies flat don't work. So I guess you're on your own. Hint: boxerwatches[dot]com instructions do work. Black mark to Amazon for blocking my comment!

text: This may not be the flashy statement that someone decided men's watches need to be, but it does everything that it needs to and then some. It has a very early 90s aesthetic to it, and offers a just-bright enough light, stopwatch, day/date, and a chirpy little alarm. Simple, easy to use, extremely clear display, and the resin watchband will outlast the wrist you strap it onto. If I had one complaint, it would be that it's a little too easy to accidentally switch this watch into 24 hour mode by pressing the alarm on/off button. That being said, it's just as easy to switch back, so it's not a big issue. Whether you're a late 90s aficionado, or just looking for a rock solid watch for less than 15.00, you could do a lot worse than this Casio.

title: Hands down the best value watch of all time.
text:
I'm into watches and have a collection of about a dozen which range from Swiss automatics to digitals like this one. I have had amazing luck these Casios in terms of reliability and water resistance. I've worn these everywhere from the ocean to the shower and never had an issue. I wouldn't necessarily recommend that someone do that, but I've never had a leak. This watch has all the features you need with a cool retro look to match.

I've owned a few rectangular G Shock watches as well. I prefer the understated looks of this F91W, however, the G Shocks in the $40 range have a few noticeable upgrades. For one, I have turned the alarm on my F91W a few times when I've fallen asleep wearing it. The issue is there are no guards around the buttons, so they are fairly easy to push accidentally. The other is the lights on G Shocks have been better in my experience.

Overall this watch is extremely easy to recommend for a feature rich, simple, inexpensive digital watch.

title: 3 Yr REVIEW Update on this Great little Watch!  GET IT >  if you need a watch
text:
This is a THREE YEAR UPDATE ON MY REVIEW.

This is one awesome little watch... IT STILL IS RUNNING ON THE SAME BATTERY IT CAME WITH. The strap is still flexible, the holes not stretched, the metal etc... all have taken a beating and it keeps on working.

My old Casio finally died after maybe 15 years... and I didn't want to spend a lot on a expensive new watch so took the plunge with this one... figured it was inexpensive enough to toss if it didn't work.

When I first got it - in fact, it didn't work. I fiddled with it, pushed every button, and finally opened it to make sure there was a battery in it... yup, there was... so fiddled with it a bit more and when nothing worked I figured I'd take it to the landfill at some point so I chucked it into a jar full of old batteries for recycling.

A few weeks later I dug it out & gave it one more chance which included smacking it on my desk top - hard. !!!!!!!!!!

IT BEGAN WORKING and has worked since! Keeps PERFECT TIME, beeps when it should and while the resin/plastic wrist strap is weird... and doesn't quite fit right - it's the watch that's important. SO - IF you are contemplating THIS LITTLE MARVEL - take the plunge and buy it.

title: If you can program a VCR this watch is for you
text:
A 23 year old design that stands the test of time. Retro, nerdy, geeky, practical, unpretentious and effective.
3 button user interface, sorry, no nfc, bluetooth, heart rate monitor, mega pixel camera, e-paper display, gps, accelerometer, barometer, compass, sd card, micro usb, laser pointer, touch screen, or microphone. Though I did hear it runs linux and java so if you jail break it and get root the sky is the limit.
The backlight is at most "quaint", think immature firefly, no indiglo here.
Was up and running with it without reading the manual, which it does come with, in 40 different languages printed in 2pt font on a low on toner printer. The only thing you might need the manual for is if you want advanced functions on the stop watch, to take a second place time But, if second place mattered to me, and you were timing it, I might insist you use a different device. And to know what the alarms settings are since the icons are so small: set time, hourly , both, and off. I am pretty sure folks at your work will hate you if you leave the hourly beep on, unless you all are seriously watching the clock and you are their big ben.

title: It‚Äôs still ticking after a couple of months use.
text:
My son LOVES his watch. He‚Äôs 5 years old and has been asking for a watch since he was 3. I promised I‚Äôd get him one when he learned his numbers. Well, I forgot, or was hesitant to invest in something that wouldn‚Äôt last, and he had to remind me for a year later. And here we are! I‚Äôve made the mistake of getting watches with the characters on them. (I‚Äôm looking at YOU Lego and Pok√©mon.) We‚Äôve bought wannabe G-Shocks. We‚Äôve been through at least 6 watches with my 2 older kids and they never lasted more than a couple of months. (Hesitancy merited!). I took a break from watch shopping because I just didn‚Äôt want to pay a lot for a kids‚Äô watch that wasn‚Äôt going to last. But my 5 year old ‚Äúneeded‚Äù a watch! He wanted a cool, big boy looking watch. I bought him an Armitron since it was a good name and we found a style he liked, and it wasn‚Äôt too pricey. The watch ended up being too big and we gave it to our 13 year old. (It‚Äôs lasted for a couple of months so far.) This brought me to the Casio. It‚Äôs bare bones, slim, water resistant, has the date and time, an alarm, and stop watch. It‚Äôs so easy to use my son can adjust the date and time on his own. He used to sleep with it under his pillow and would put it on every morning. Now he sleeps with it on but loosens it so his skin can ‚Äúbreathe‚Äù at my behest. He tells everyone about his watch. It‚Äôs endured more than a couple of months so far. Fingers crossed to Casio still being quality.

The pics include a size comparison of this Casio and the Casio Men's W800H-1AV Classic Sport Watch with Black Band, and the Armitron Sport Men's Digital Chronograph Resin Strap Watch, 40/8284. They fit my 5, 11, and 13 year old boys well, respectively.

text:
I think these are the cheapest brand name watches you can buy in the US. Yet they're durable and seem to be reliable. Water resistance is real and it can be kicked around and banged about without breaking.

LED illumination is weak, not like newer watches that glow aqua throughout the face. And LED readout doesn't have the crisp, high contrast readout of newer watches. This design came out around 1990 and I don't think they have updated the technology in any way, for good and bad.

I recommend it because it's so unobtrusive and cheap to buy. But the more expensive models are easier to read and do have better night illumination.

title: It's a great little watch that is packed with useful features
text:
I originally bought this watch because the company I worked for at the time, timed breaks down to the second. If you were so much as a second late, you would be written up and given a warning.

It's a great little watch that is packed with useful features, I find the alarm function particularly useful as it has a very distinct pitch which is difficult to sleep through. The AM/PM marker is important to note though, as I have to cycle through 12 hour markers to change the alarm. The day and date feature is another great one to have, as it saves the guess work of remembering what day of the week and date of the month I am currently on. This comes especially in handy when filling out and completing paperwork.

The band is very comfortable to wear, my only recommendation is an occasional cleaning as it has a tendency to accumulate residue from dead skin and sweat, which can lead to an uncomfortable rash if not otherwise addressed.

title: The perfect watch
text: I just received this watch today, and it felt wonderful putting it on my wrist. The band is very comfortable and easy to adjust, it does not slide up and down my wrist. Also, the watch is easy to set up and very easy to use. It also  has a built in light feature, so it will glow in the dark when you press the button. This watch is only $10 and its value is far more than that. It has a very classic look for digital watches and will get the job done right.  I believe if you simply want to watch that fits comfortably, and tells you the time, then you will be most pleased with this model. I can't say enough good things about this watch, best watch I have ever owned so far. Moreover, because it is  inexpensive if anything ever happens to it, replacing it would not cost an arm and a leg. The only thing it lacks, would be beauty. However, if you desire a Watch for its functionality and utilitarianism, this is the right watch for you. After all, with it being black in color, it will match anything you wear.

title: Great watch at a great price
text: The first time I ever got a F91W1 was when I was in the 10th grade. My grandfather gave me this watch because I was planning on going on a 22 day Alpine back packing trip in the Sierra Nevada and would need a watch. This watch was perfect. Over the course of my trip, I went swimming in waterfalls, freezing cold lakes and rapids. The watch was resistant to water damage through and through. Not a day went by that I didn't wear the watch. I slept with the watch every night and by the end of the trip, I had a watch tan lol. Unfortunately, I lost the watch when I came home. So I bought a new one about 5 months ago from Amazon. This new watch is great and doesn't have any of the wear that my old one had (duh). The old one definitely had a lot of character to it but this one is just as awesome, for a great price too! The watch is also pretty fashionable amongst my peers. I always hear compliments about it. The simple design of the watch is definitely a step up to all the bulky Casio G-Shocks that everyone at my school wears. Its also very sporty, I wear it whenever i go out for a run or hike. Overall, the watch is great for casual or sport wear. It is a fully functional, simple watch that can take a beating. At this price, it is definitely a steal. I would recommend this watch to anyone.

title: pretty good for the price
text:
You can‚Äôt really beat it for the price. I‚Äôm an avid surfer and swimmer, and I can‚Äôt tell you how many other cheap watches I‚Äôve ruined by testing my luck in the water. This one lasted about a year of surfing 2-3 times a week. I wish it lasted longer, but overall I think that‚Äôs a pretty good showing for a watch that‚Äôs under $20.

My only complaint would be that it‚Äôs easy to accidentally push the buttons when flexing your wrist. I don‚Äôt even take it off when sleeping, so this sometimes resulted in accidentally setting off the alarm in the middle of the night. Sometimes I would have to walk into another room to fix the alarm settings without waking up my girlfriend. If you just take it off before sleeping that would easily avoid this problem.

Summary: Does it look cool? Not really. Does it track the tides, or your heart rate, or altitude? Absolutely not. Is it perfect? No. Will it last forever? Also no. But does it keep good time, cost less than $20, and stand up to a decent amount of abuse, including water? Yeah, it does.

title: I only gave it 4 stars because of the buttons
text:
I found the buttons stick out too much which makes it too easy for the buttons to depress through simple wrist flexing and physical movement. I also don't like the fact that by pressing one button it brings up the mode where the seconds can be reset to zero. This has cause me a few problems.

Otherwise, it is an excellent, but unattractive watch. I am not a watch guy. The only reason I bought this watch was because I was getting married in Jamaica and I couldn't rely on my cellphone to keep track of time. The resort we were at had specific times that certain things opened and closed. I chose this watch online because of how light it was and how thin it was. I also have a small wrist so a big watch would look stupid on me.

This watch has been in the Caribbean, the pools and I beat it up at work building airplanes. About 5 minutes ago I took it out of the front load washer after an hour and 7 minute wash cycle. No problems. It got mixed up with my clothes and I couldn't find it for a few days.

title: A very solid every day watch. Pretty small though.
text:
I went with this watch because I was previously using a smart watch daily, but was growing tired of constantly having to charge it and having it run out of battery. When I first received the watch, I was a little surprised with how small it was. The face of the watch is just under the size of a quarter (see the attached picture), so if you're on the bigger side, this might look really small on you. The wrist strap included, as I can't imagine it being comfortable on those who have bigger wrists.

The watch itself is comfortable, and I barely notice that I'm wearing it. It is easy to read during the day, and I have found the month / date feature to be super useful as I'm constantly forgetting what day it is. Setting the watch is really easy, and I like that you can easily switch between 24 hour and 12 hour mode.

The built in light is just OK. The light really only lights up one side of the watch which can make it a challenge to read at night if your eyes aren't adjusted.

All in all, not too much to complain about given the price point. If those things aren't deal breakers for you, the watch is a really solid value, and great for every day wear.

And most people will never use most of those features anyways. This watch is the epitome of a beater watch. It's ten bucks! Get a new one! Not that you even have to. I beat up watches pretty regularly, and this one has stood there test of time. Not to mention it's even pretty iconic on the watch world. You cannot go wrong with this watch.

title: strap's too short

I think the first one I bought cost twelve dollars, so this one's cheaper today, when you take into consideration how the U.S. has devalued the currency since then.  Only real problem is that the strap is too short for an adult man - when they first came out, they had a longer strap that you could trim if it was too long.

text: This trusty watch sits on my wrist for weeks at a time.  I wear it in the shower, gardening, playing with the dog, working on cars, everywhere! title: Pictures Don't Do It Justice
text: The green color is beautiful.  Much more shiny and rich in person.  As for performance the F-91W is a classic beater watch.  For under $20 you get a reliable, comfortable, and attractive time piece.  All functions are very basic on this, so don't expect a lot.  The stopwatch only times up to 1 hour, and there is no timer function.  Water resistance is good.  I shower in mine all the time, but I don't know how well it would do swimming or bathing.  I have not tried submerging it for extended periods.  Overall great value and a classic look.

Also, occasionally I would accidentally take it out of time mode, and had to fumble to get it back.  And when I accidentally caused it to chime every hour, I had to find a Casio aficionado to fix it -- fortunately, Casio is a popular brand with a pretty consistent button layout, so I found someone who had read the manual in short order.

title: Good, cheap, and waterproof - if it doesn't crack
text:
EDIT - thought I was in the clear, but the replacement watch just took a bit longer to show the exact same issue.

Worn a total of two times - first time, I noticed a tiny hairline crack along the right edge of the case that started spreading onto the watch face (photo 1). This crack spread and started branching, fully across the face and down it the second and final time I wore it (photo 2). It's been sitting on my dresser, untouched, where the face continues to destroy itself (photo 3). I bought this to wear while kayaking, and there's no way this is water resistant now! Manufacturing defect - probably? I remember my dad would wear these for years without issue. Amazon was great with sending me out a replacement though, and it's a timelessy-designed digital watch at an incredible price point - so I'm hoping this replacement fares better!

title: Classically cool (or uncool)
text:
A steady workhorse. No frills but plenty of function. It's reliable, comfortable, and lightweight. Its weakness is its old-school light. It's enough for you to make out the time in the dark, but it might take a little squinting to do it. If being able to easily check the time in the dark is important, go with the F105W-1A.

I think it looks better with a NATO band. An 18mm band fits. But if you're changing the band be aware that the pins are not spring pins. And a traditional pin tool is too big to push them out. The result was using a LOT of force to push the pins out. Be sure to push in the direction of the arrow on the band.

title: Tiny, But Works Well
text: I got this on a lightning deal for seven bucks. Love all things Casio and have been looking for a cheap knockabout watch. It's a nice watch, very comfortable, and has only lost about half a second in the five days since I set it against one of my atomic G-Shock models. That works out to 3 seconds a month accuracy, which is great for such an inexpensive and basic watch. All hail Casio. However, just one problem from my perspective - the watch is just way too tiny. I am a smallish guy with small wrists, and it still is way too small. The band is long enough, it's the body of the watch. I can't believe this is being sold as a men's watch - it is far more suitable for children or small-size women. I'm going to just give this to my very petite girlfriend, it'll be perfect for her.

title: It's just good cheap gear
text: Light, tough, accurate, reliable, and practically disposable. More accurate than a Rolex, more affordable than a Timex, small wonder these humble little watches are the darling of cash strapped GIs and working people everywhere. For three decades now, this one has been the one that checks the square of a bare bones "tool watch". So the backlight is kind of weak,  if it's really dark then it's really bright enough. So it doesn't have a countdown timer. Improvise and use the stopwatch or alarm instead. So you can't drive a truck over it like you can a G Shock. Big deal, let a truck drive over you and see how you make out.  I save my "nice" watches for when I want to "dress up".  When it's time to mow the yard, go for a hike or hit the beach, I strap on old reliable. Why not?  If I wind up breaking or losing it, I'll just grab another one and press on. It's not wrist jewelry, it's gear, good cheap gear.

title: Why do I own any other watches?
text:
This watch is everything you need. It's functional. It's subtle. It's oddly beautiful. It just works. Working from home due to COVID has made my professional dress attire increasingly casual. I felt weird wearing my nicer watches while working from home. I found myself wanting a more stripped down, no nonsense watch as the days and weeks past.

That's when I saw Ewan McGregor wearing one of these on his Long Way Up series. I thought if a watch like this is good enough for him then it has to be good enough for everyone.

I immediately removed the original band and put on an 18mm Martini livery-themed NATO strap to spice this watch up. I think the blues on the strap go great with the blue ring on the dial.

I haven't tested this watch's water resistance but I don't plan on it because it doesn't look like it's made for water. But for working at my desk and being around the house, this is the perfect watch.

text: Over the past 30 years, I've owned 4 of these watches. It's always been around/less than $10. Last one I bought was about 6 years ago and paid $8 (I see now it's under $17). Watches have always kept perfect time. I wear it as a leisure/work around the home/weekend watch (not a dress watch). The light still illuminates the face. My only beef is when the time changes (fall/behind & spring/ahead), it's a PITA to make the adjustments. It's not the easiest watch to do this with (especially when you lose the instruction sheet). What normally happens is the band wears out before the battery. Although, this last band is wearing well. If you want a cheap/simple/no maintenance watch, that keeps perfect time, buy this. Kudos to Casio who have kept this watch in inventory but shame on them for making it a bit more expensive to buy. No one can tell me the cost to make this watch has almost doubled, since I last bought it.

title: Great watch for this cheap? How does Casio do it?

Has time, am/pm or 24hr time on face along with Day (e.g., FR) and date (just the day, e.g. 31). Easy to set and easy to use alarm or stop watch. This watch is so light and comfortable I really do not realize I am wearing a watch.  I hope they continue to make these.  If I destroy or lose it I will just buy another and so on. title: Basic, Solid Digital Watch
text:
This my first "real watch" back when I was a kid, and I decided to pick up another when I needed something that was just going to keep the time for me. I was not disappointed. This watch does a superb job of keeping accurate time, is water resistant (I have worn it in the shower with no issues) and durable enough for every-day use.

The one drawback for me is that the face scratches easily; however, this is more of a cosmetic issue and does not affect my ability to use the watch.

title: This is an astoundingly good watch for $15
text:
I've worn this watch every day for a year. Just keeps ticking (well not really, it's digital). It may say "water resistant," but it's waterproof enough to take swimming. I've even gone to over 15m deep and had no trouble, but I still wouldn't take it on a serious scuba dive. The strap is holding up well, though on previous iterations of this watch I've had that's the first thing to go. It's small and thin enough that I'll often wear it for weeks straight without remembering to take it off.

My only gripe, which isn't even enough to take off a star since this is an astoundingly good watch for $15, is that it doesn't have a countdown timer which I believe previous iterations of the F91W had (my last one did). It was handy for workouts and chores like laundry, but really you can't expect much more out of a watch that's already worth its weight in gold.

title: humbling
text:
As I am in my early 30's things like fancy watches, clothes, and cars are being replaced with savings, marriage, vacations, and retirement. As someone who used to love fossil, nixon, tag heuer, and other fancy watches, I wanted to find the cheapest watch possible that can still do the job.

I am purging all my fancy things and replacing them with items that are usable and practical. I guess I am becoming my dad? So I went with this little guy and it is a great watch when I don't want to use my apple watch (ironically given to me as a gift). This is going to be my every day wear as it is a constant reminder to me that I have to continue to be practical in my spending. I thought the size would be a problem but I have small wrists, I can see how it would be a problem if I had bigger ones and would definitely not go with this watch. The light doesn't really bother me as what can you expect from a 10 dollar watch. I mean it's 10 dollars! Not even sure how they make money selling this watch, haha.

5/5

title: Best Watch Ever Made
text:
I have a lot of watches, including some very expensive ones. At the end of the day though, this one is still my favorite. It's not super pretty, it's not a piece of mechanical craftsmanship and art, but it weighs absolutely nothing and it tells you the time and date and it's nearly bulletproof. I've taken this down to 45 meters below sea level and it still lights right up and tells you that it's 3PM. If you do somehow manage to break it, by running it over with a train or something, it costs $10 to replace.

After a few years the strap broke while I was in Vietnam and I couldn't find a genuine Casio to replace it and ended up paying $12 ($2 more than the cost of a real one with shipping!) for a fake one so I could swap out the strap. Both the fake and the strap broke a few weeks later. I wasn't ready to give up on this guy, and managed to get a genuine replacement strap in Kuala Lumpur for $5. Yes, I could have just bought 2 new ones from Amazon for the combined cost of the replacement parts, but that's beside the point! And anyway, it's a lot less than the $500 or so just to service a fancy chronometer I mostly leave in the drawer.

title: Has the features I need at the lowest cost
text:
I could never wear a fancy watch. That's just not me.

I had a different Casio for two years. When the band finally split I discovered what I'd been afraid of. A new band would've cost almost as much as a new watch. Oh, well...

This model was less than the one I was replacing, but it does exactly what I need. It tells the time, the date, the day of the week, and a.m./p.m. Although it doesn't tell the month, I'd be in trouble if I couldn't figure that out on my own.

The directions were too small for me to read easily, but within five minutes I'd found the directions online. I copied and pasted them into a Word document for future reference.

This watch is also a tiny bit smaller than my previous one, and I'm glad it is. I have small hands and wrists and it just looks a little better than a larger watch.

I just hope this band will last two years like the previous one.

text: A great watch. I wanted something simple to keep track of time, and this does it. I didn't want anything fancy. I was sick of pulling out my huge phone for what used to be a simple task. Bought one for my boyfriend as well, and he would agree. Will replace as necessary.

title: Gym and low key day watch
text:
This is my go to watch for when I'm climbing at the rock gym. There isn't a clock at the gym and I don't want to wear my fitness tracker or anything else that I know would get scratched or banged up while climbing. This watch is very sturdy while still being slim and lightweight. I also like to wear it if I'm going hiking or if I am feeling old-school-cool. I have a few fancier watches but this watch is the one that people remark on the most for its retro look. The light function on it is pretty weak but works in a pinch. The timer is great if I just want to time my runs. The alarm function is surprisingly loud and effective! However the alarm turns itself off after 30 seconds so I wouldn't depend on it.

All in all, you can't go wrong with this watch and it has quickly become my favorite for casual days.

title: Shame - was the best watch ever, it is awful now
text:
I LOVED this watch. I wore this model for 5 straight years without removal - maybe a every few months to clean - took showers with it, swam in the ocean, swimming in pools, etc. It held up like a champ; I never had a problem with it. The day/dates/alarms function and layout is simply the best. Alas, the rubber wrist strap eventually broke and I had to buy a new one.

I've purchased four of these watches in the past year. Unfortunately within a couple of weeks of showering with it on, the face starts to fog up with moisture. It eventually turns into water drops and the face dies. I loved this watch so much that I bought three more, hoping that I got a dud. I live in Philadelphia and it was a humid summer. I made sure not to shower in the watch to prevent the moisture build-up, but the humidity alone - and perhaps very minimal splashing from hand-washing? - caused moisture to sneak into the watch face. I am very upset that I cannot wear this model any longer and will have to find an alternative that is more water resistant. I've never left reviews but I truly did love this watch and my heart is too broken to keep quiet.

It hurts me to advise that folks should stay away from this item.

title: Will probably buy another one
text:
I had something very much like this 25 years ago in college and it served me well. I like the simplicity and versatility; I would like it even better if it had fewer colorful markings (for wear with dark clothes). It arrived quickly and worked perfectly; I used it swimming at the YMCA and so on. And at about $10, it's hard to go wrong!

The watch lost a star because when I took it swimming in the ocean, and used the timer functions, that evening the watch developed some condensation on the inside, and 2-3 days later it stopped working. Maybe I had a loose seal. I'm going to get the G-Shock (bought one of those in 1990 and it lasted well over a decade of heavy use); if it's too bulky for the office then I'll get this model again.

UPDATE 8/21/2015: I did in fact buy another one some time ago; it's still cheap, very functional, and understated enough that I can wear it to work in an office setting. And maybe I just assumed that it was waterproof last time, but I now notice that it says "Water Resistant" on the back of the watch, so my bad for taking it into the ocean! It would be silly to dock it for not being water proof since in addition to it saying so on the watch, the web page says resistant rather than proof, so I'm changing it from four to five stars.

It is EXTREMELY light weight (almost impossible to feel on your wrist unless you have it so tight it is cutting off circulation which you shouldn't be doing anyway). If it is tightened properly, you cannot feel it. The time is easy to read. The band is plastic, meaning it is waterproof and you don't have to take it off to wash your hands (like I was having to do with all my leather bands and getting annoyed). Also shows the day and the date, which is super helpful during a hectic work week when everything starts to blur together.

Has a retro 1980s vibe that is totally in right now with Stranger Things and hipsters and I've gotten a lot of compliments on it. Somehow, after all of these features, the watch still costs only $9. Thus, I offer this watch up as the very best value in any watches anywhere. I thought my $20 Timex was a good value, but after buying this watch the Timex just sits in my drawer since it seems so comparatively heavy, high maintenance (canvas band that starts to smell funky after a few weeks and needs watching). I wear this watch daily and get a weird kick out of putting it on. The best $9 I have spent in a long time. Has an aesthetic that is 100% functional/pragmatic, which just makes it a fun thing to use. I wish I had purchased this watch YEARS ago. I am excited about using this watch to backpack since I am not afraid about it being stolen, quickly tells me the time (digital), won't absorb odors or show dirt, and weighs nothing.

Bad:
The one thing I wish this watch had was an Indiglo feature like Timex watches have, since the light up feature on this watch is sufficient to see, but not nearly as nice as Timex Indiglo.

title: 90's Nostalgia and a Great Watch for Only $12
text: I wore a Casio F-91W watch in the 90's and I loved it as it fit perfectly under a dress shirt but also worked so well as a casual watch, and it was indestructible.  It never needed a battery and kept perfect time for many years.  Eventually the band broke and by then, my cell phone told the time and I stopped wearing a watch.  I got back into watches 8 years ago and I now have a small collection.  I had completely forgotten about the F-91W until I saw it online recently.  Wow, Casio has been making the same watch since 1989!  It is new and retro at the same time.  I ordered one as soon as I saw it and I absolutely love my new one.  It is 1990 all over again and the price of nostalgia was a mere $12.  It is smaller and lighter than I remember (but that is probably because modern watches are large and heavy).  It is a pleasure to wear as most of the time I forget I have it on my wrist.  You can pay thousands of times more for a watch but this is all you need if you just want a dependable watch that will accurately tell you the time.  Everyone should have a F-91W in their collection, no matter if you only own one watch or you own a thousand.  It is an iconic watch for less $ than you will spend for lunch.

title: The icon lives on
text:
I got over smartwatches pretty fast since IMO having to dock a watch every two days kind of defeats the purpose of a reliable timepiece. I don't even care that this makes me sound old, anyone with a similar opinion will love this watch since it's about 1/20th of the price and won't need a recharge for about 7 years.

Plus it's classic style is known and distinguished among generations, so you get style points without going broke, even if you decide to keep a couple extras in different colors.

My job is very hands on, so the low profile durability on the wrist is another serious win. I'll occasionally even sleep with this thing on just from forgetting to take it off.

One last note on the backlight. This has the tiny side LED (green bulb). I debated getting the illuminator versions (the solid blue backlight) since they're brighter and more even-lit. But you don't get the face color options when going for the illuminator style backlight (since the f91w in particular wasn't made with illuminators), and trust me, you don't need it unless it's nearly pitch black, and the green light is adequate the few times you would need it, the panels alone are just as easy to read as a sheet of paper.

title: Amazing watch for $10.
text:
I have had my F-91w for several years. My son also has one. You‚Äôll see that my positive comments are similar to those of other reviewers:
- Comfortable and almost weightless. Feels like it‚Äôs not there.
- The perfect set of features for a digital watch: Time; 24-hr (military) time; optional hourly beep; optional daily alarm; stop watch w/ 1/100th of second timing; light.
- According to Casio, this is not really a water resistant watch‚Äî splashes only, I believe. However, my son & I have worn ours swimming in fresh water and salt water dozens of times, often for over an hour at a time. No damage at all.

My only complaint: The light. Back when I owned my early Casios (mid-1980s), the ‚Äúbacklights‚Äù were dim and weak yellowish lights that shone from one side of the display and almost didn‚Äôt light up the opposite side of the display. That‚Äôs how this light is. This weak feature might not matter to you, but I sleep in my watch and am in the habit of looking at it if I wake up at night. The light almost doesn‚Äôt light up the whole face. If the watch‚Äôs light is important to you, consider the Casio F-105, which is the same exact watch (size/shape/features) as the F-91w, but for $3 more gives you a blue light that illuminates the entire screen uniformly. I have another Casio watche with this type of light and it‚Äôs amazing. So if the weak light doesn‚Äôt matter, get this for $10. For a much better light, get the F-105 for $13.

title: A True Classic.  The Patek Philippe of Digital Watches
text:
This is probably the most practical watch one can own. Great job Casio!

I do not understand the current trend of ‚Äúcookie on a strap‚Äù when it comes to watches. You really want an 8 ounce watch made from steel salvaged from a sunken ship? This watch confidently bucks that trend both in size but also in practical value. The F91 is for those with more brains than money.

If you take a look back in watch history when watches were made to tell time and not function as high fashion, watches were smaller. The common man sized watch was about 35mm wide. Guess how wide the F91 is, yup, about 35mm wide. Do you suppose there might have been a reason watches were smaller? Perhaps weight and comfort? Ever try wearing one of the ‚Äúcookie on a strap‚Äù watches with a long sleeved shirt or with gloves? As Dr. Phil would say, ‚Äúhow‚Äôs that working out for you?‚Äù.

The F91 fits under shirts easily and doesn‚Äôt catch on the cuff. It‚Äôs so light you forget it‚Äôs on your wrist, unlike a Seiko monster I once owned that I could not wait to take off. After you have forgotten it‚Äôs on your wrist, no reason to baby it. It‚Äôs water resistant and will survive getting knocked around just fine.

Unlike our smart watches of today, battery life is measured in years, not hours. I can‚Äôt believe I didn‚Äôt get one sooner and I can‚Äôt believe people by watches that won‚Äôt run more than 18 - 24 hours without a power source to charge the battery. That‚Äôs not progress, that‚Äôs regress. Funny how with a enough marketing some believe black is really white and the moon is just the sun at night.

title: How Can a Classic Be Refused?
text:
The Casio F-91W. One can easily spend twice, if not more than what this watch is selling for, on far more useless items.

For under twenty bucks, you get the genuine classic that‚Äôs been around for a little more than a couple decades now. Despite its ties to more sinister incidents in history not-so-long ago, it is still a really cool watch!

The watch and all its functions are operated by three buttons. Doesn‚Äôt take much to learn how to set and use it. Its simple functionality is why it‚Äôs become a favorite in my watch collection.

Thirty something millimeters is a bit on the small side, but it‚Äôs not so bad. It still has presence regardless of its small case, and super light weight. Yea, once you have it on, you could forget you‚Äôre wearing it.

The resin strap isn‚Äôt the best. I expect to replace it sooner rather than later. The backlight is a joke. Could barely read the display in darkness, but it‚Äôs clear and legible otherwise.

I‚Äôm not gonna vouch for the WR. I‚Äôve heard some people go swimming with it, some swear not to go anywhere near liquid with it on.

For the money, wide availability, simplicity, and options of colors to cater to your style, I think it‚Äôs a watch anyone can own and appreciate; unless if you‚Äôre one of those watch snobs who considers anything less than Rolex as garbage, stay away from this watch.

title: A great reliable inexpensive retro style watch
text: I bought this watch at a big box store roughly a year ago for just over $15.00. I previously owned similar watches like this one back in the 80s. It is a fine inexpensive and nice retro digital watch. It is accurate and loses maybe 15 seconds or so each month. The low gloss gray silver case finish and face black strap give it a nice clean monochromatic look. It is easy to read. The back light shines from the left and is dim on the minutes digits in less than pitch black rooms but reads easily in very dark rooms and areas. It can be worn for almost any occasion but would seem best suited for daily wear, to work, recreation, exercising, in the garden, working on the car, etc. If it is used in situations where it is bumped into walls or objects it will scuff and scratch the case easily. The comfortable plastic strap is nice and when it wears out it can be replaced with an inexpensive Nato strap or could even be replaced with a new F-91W watch altogether at this low price. I highly recommend this watch. You cant go wrong with this one. It brings style,accuracy, affordability,comfort and utility all together in one package.

I mean someone who wants a simple, reliable, cheap watch. This watch tells you the time, day of week, and date at a glance. The strap is comfortable and doesn't absorb sweat or become discolored. It's only after over 2 years of wearing this watch every waking moment that the strap is finally starting to break. For a little over $10 I'd say that's a good deal.

title: This Watch is a Keeper
text:
I bought this watch 10 years ago because it's waterproof and I needed it for swimming. I swim at least three days a week, 52 weeks a year. I use it for both time and the stopwatch feature, which is invaluable for swimming and so many other uses, such as cook timing, etc. This watch keeps perfect time, it never leaked, the stopwatch is great, and it has more features that I don't even use. I'm replacing it now because the strap finally broke. I really can't complain because I paid $14 and it lasted for ten years. Same battery!. Even if the strap could be replaced it would cost more than a new watch.

You can't beat this watch for the price and it's utility value.

UPDATE AFTER RECEIVING WATCH. I thought I was buying an identical watch to the one I purchased 10 years ago, but I was somewhat disappointed. The new watch is essentially identical to the old watch, but HALF the size, so everything is smaller, including the display. It works the same and has all the same features, but the watch is literally half the size of the old one. That was a disappointment. I'm keeping the watch for everyday use and for swimming laps, but I miss the larger size of the old watch.

I changed my rating from 5 to 4 stars.

title: Casio digital watches are always reliable. F91W has the green firefly light.
text:
I have been buying the Casio Digital watches since the 1980's. I won't wear any other kind of watch. The resin bands are so comfortable and smooth to wear. Forget other watches that have that steel stretchy band that grabs and pulls the hair on your wrist. Casio watches don't do that. If your resin band cracks or breaks, you can always buy another band from PerFit, according to the model number of your watch, from Amazon or directly from the Casio company.
I now prefer this Quartz digital F-91W model because it is always available and it has what I call a green "firefly" light you can turn on to see what time it is in the darken movie theater. This model IS water resistant. There is an alarm you can set to the time you want it to beep. This watch is always correct to +/- 30 seconds per month. You can always reset the time of this watch down to the very second. There is an alarm you can set to beep every hour (choice of on or off) and set to an exact time. Choose 12-hour or 24-hour (military) reading. Auto calendar you can set day and date. You can even set it to "Leap Day ' (2-29).
Be sure to read the instructions to setting your watch for the first time before you wear it. Instructions are printed in English and 3 other languages.
Includes one-year warranty.
Add this Casio watch to your Amazon Wish List so you can buy another one for yourself or as a gift. Great gift for a father or grandfather to give to your sons. Casio makes a pink watch for the daughters too.

title: Tried and True Design
text: I wanted to try this watch for two reasons: one is that I have a hard time finding a watch that doesn‚Äôt look extra large on my extra small wrists. The other is that I wanted something cheap I can wear while I‚Äôm at work (restocking large heavy boxes) without care of it getting scuffed. It handles both of these tasks fairly well so far! The hourly chime has actually been a lot nicer than I thought it would be for work cause it reminds me of any tasks that need to be completed. I just turn off the chime when I return home so it doesn‚Äôt go off and drive me crazy when I‚Äôm trying to go to bed! The alarm is nice and I wake up to it and I use it as a back up to my phones alarm clock. The backlight works perfectly fine for my needs as I‚Äôm usually using it in the middle of the night and I‚Äôm wondering how long it has been since I started to try to fall asleep and I go ‚Äúreally, That long?!‚Äù It has gotten a few scuffs over the course of work, but nothing that‚Äôs too noticeable/in your face and with a watch like this I think the scratches just adds to its character. I have been caught in the rain and have Had times when I had to wash my entire arm along with the watch and it has held up to all the soaking though I don‚Äôt know how it would hold up in complete submersion. The main selling point is the price though and for all that it can do I will definitely be looking into more Casio products in the future when I am looking for quality at a reasonable price. Maybe I‚Äôll be fancy and look at one with a metal band.

title: Perfect gift for time-conscious son
text: My wife suggested getting a watch like this as a gift for our 8-year old son, and it has turned out to be ideal.  Looks and functions just like the Casio I had at about the same age -- including light and timer functions (down to the hundredth of a second).  Fits his wrist well (on one of the tightest settings), so I can see how some have complained that the band is too small.  The face of the watch is just the right size -- not too big, not too small.  He loves to be able to compare his watch with all the clocks in his school.  It also helps him stay on task for specific amounts of time.  One day, he accidentally switched it to military time, which caused him some temporary panic ("It says 14:30! It's broken!"), but that became an opportunity to learn about the 24-hour clock.  Great deal on a great watch.

title: My son loves it!

After he came back he told me he loves it and plans to wear it to school and other places where a cell phone is not allowed.  I used to wear a Casio all the time when I was younger and I am glad to see that the quality is still the same and my son is eager to continue the tradition.

title: Great watch, wimpy watch band
text:
This is the third F91W-1 watch that I have owned. My previous one still functions as a watch, but the band broke after I had worn it daily for two years. I ordered a whole new watch because its Amazon price was only a little more than $10--about twice the cost of a replacement band from Amazon.

The watch itself is great--5 stars. This is a no-nonsense watch which gives you the time, date, a stopwatch, and an alarm. The functions are simple to access and the battery life is great. I have worn it while sweating in the gym or working in the yard, and it seems to survive the perspiration just fine.

The watch band doesn't last more than a couple of years, however--3 stars. The long part that threads through the buckle cracks where it rests under the buckle. I have tried replacing the band myself. On the first occasion I was successful, but on the second I broke the watch case because I didn't have the correct tools. If you buy the band in a store, the sales person may put the new band on for you, but you may pay more for the band than the cost of the new watch on Amazon.

It's worth buying the watch. How you deal with a broken band after two years is a toss-up.

title: One of the best watches ever made regardless of price
text: I own several watches but this is the one I go to most often. It has just about everything you need in a watch (accurate time, the date, a stop watch, and an alarm) while being so small and light that you forget you're wearing it. Even if you spent tens of thousands of dollars on a different watch, it is unlikely that it would be anywhere near as comfortable as this one. What people say about the light is mostly true. It isn't very bright. That said, it is still bright enough to read the time when it's dark. There are times when a super bright light is not preferred, especially when your eyes are light sensitive because you've been sleeping or have been in a dark area for a while.

title: Worn every day for 2 years AND abused
text:
First things first, it is hard for me to find a watch that doesn't look bulky on my small wrists, and this watch achieves just that. The face is small enough to fit comfortably on my wrist without being too big or small. That being said, I've had this watch for almost two years and it's still kicking. I've abused this thing, brought it in the ocean, in pools, I've scratched this thing up from carrying a skateboard, I've thrown this watch everywhere, I've slammed it down on various surfaces, I brought it to a summer camp, and it still holds up. The gold paint does wear away over time, but that's probably a result of the way I wear it (with the face on the inside of my wrist) so it rubs against everything. It still looks fine without the gold paint because the plastic underneath is an off-white color. The strap is still going strong, no cracks or tears or any signs of weakness. I wear this watch every day and I've done that for the past two years and I thoroughly believe that this watch will last a lot longer than that. It tells you everything you need to know, the time, and the date. Warning: You WILL have to change the date after February because it doesn't account for the missing days. No big deal though, this watch is so simple that you can change anything on the face of it in just a few seconds. Because of the way I wear the watch (this is my fault, not the watch) I often have to toggle it from 24 hr time to standard 12 because that button always gets accidentally pressed.
PROS:
Cheap, durable as ****, looks really clean, light, perfect for small wrists
CONS:
You will have to change the date like once a year for February
