title: Perfect basic watch
text:
***Year update: Still rocking this little thing. It's looking a little worn, but I don't baby it. The plastic that the strap is pinned into actually somehow broke one night. I was devastated, but I was able to superglue it back together and it's held together since (~about 6 months now). My only complaint is that mine gains time at about a rate of about 3 seconds/week. Nothing terrible considering the price, but it's painfully obvious when I compare it to the Wave Ceptor (my atomic time keeper)

I'll preface this buy disclaiming that the main reason I bought this watch was because of all the jokes about it being linked to.... less savory types. However, I did need a cheaper watch than my Wave Ceptor that I wouldn't mind wearing every day and wouldn't care about keeping it looking nice. This watch fits the bill. It's very lightweight and fits my small wrists without a problem. It has all the basic functions you can want out of a digital watch and has an almost timeless look to it. The display is easy to read and the light is nice and bright in the dark. My only complaint is that is you enable the hour beep, it's rather loud. It was a feature I was looking forward to using, but I don't want to disturb people around me so it remains turned off. I'd easily buy this again at around $10 if something were to happen to this watch.

title: Retro and iconic? I'll take one!
text:
It looks small even on my skinny wrist, but I love it, it is so retro looking!

EDIT: Some time has passed so I'll give some more of my opinions...
-The light on the display isn't the brightest but you'll still be able to tell time in pitch darkness however it only illuminates from the left side of the watch, not the whole thing.
-The band is decent; I can wear it up to the sixth hole; any less and it'd be uncomfortable, any more and it would slip around my wrist. I recommend you wear it loose enough that air can pass through but so that it won't slip around cause it gets sweaty.
-I have bumped it against a few hard surfaces and there are no marks or scratches.
-With the push of a button on the lower right side it switches interchangeably from standard to military time.
-Have not tested the alarm, since I just use my phone for that.
-Design looks straight from the late 80s early 90s which is a plus.
-How waterproof is it? Well I have SEEN a video of someone blasting it with a high pressure water hose and it still worked.
All in all it is an inexpensive, dependable, durable watch that is a little on the small side, but you get used to it. I want to upgrade it with a 18mm(the only size that fits) NATO strap in the future to give it more flare.

title: Economical and accurate watch
text:
This review is in two parts: First, the timepiece itself is reasonably accurate and the battery does last a long time. The only design flaw is the omission of a month display. Sure, most of us know what the current month is, but why not also have it digitally displayed beside the day of month on the face of this watch?
The second part of review is the strap that comes with this watch. These straps are made from a man-made material that slowly grows more and more brittle over time. It will eventually break, guaranteed. This usually happens near the point where the left and right straps buckle together. The watch itself will outlast the original strap plus a couple of replacement straps. I have a supply of perfectly good digital watches still keeping time, but now sitting in a storage drawer because I can no longer find suitable straps. Even if I could, they are nearly as expensive as a brand new watch. So, I purchase another $12 Casio watch because they are good for everyday use.
Speaking of straps: the strap on this watch is awful. The reason for this is the loop that secures the end of strap in place after putting watch on your wrist. The loop is floating, that is, it is not fixed in any one position on the strap. This causes it to move out of position and no longer keeps end of strap secured. That means the strap is forever catching on everything and forcing the watch to rotate around on your wrist. If you like aggravation, you'll love this strap.

title: The world's most popular watch?
text:
I bought my Casio F-91W 20 years ago for less than the price of dinner out. I was a young teenager and wanted a fashion neutral watch that would show seconds on the main display as well as the day of the week and day of the month. I still wear the same F-91W every day. I replaced the battery once in 20 years. My watch is dependably fast by 1 second per week so as long as I set it back by about 10 seconds every 2-3 months it keeps almost perfect time.

A tried and true design, Casio has not changed it for at least two decades now. Because of its low cost, simplicity, reliability, wide availability, optional 24-hour time display, and alarm capability this watch is commonly used by people of both genders throughout the world, including third world cities and remote villages.

It is no surprise that the Casio F-91W is apparently standard issue to graduates of al-Qaeda's Al Farouq training camp and has been used by others for triggering time bombs. Surprisingly, possession of the watch was used by the US military as justification for detention of enemy combatants at the Guantanamo Bay prison camp.

With its reliability and wide availability it is possible that this is the world's most popular watch.

title: For roughly $10, it‚Äôs pretty tough to beat for someone looking for practical timekeeping, and who isn‚Äôt concerned with the lates
text: Everything written about this watch is true. It‚Äôs cheap. It‚Äôs ugly. It just plain works. I bought one roughly 7 years ago, and it‚Äôs still working today. When I bought it, I was working at an industrial recycling plant. I worked long hours, doing demanding physical labor in hot environments, handling corrosive chemicals. I needed a watch that could stand up to the abuse, and preferably one cheap enough that I won‚Äôt have lost much, if it did break. I saw the Casio F91W-1 and - for around $10 - figured it might just do. I wore that watch every day, in 100+ degree work environments. I wore it when I shoveled ton after ton of sludge by hand. I wore it when I scraped out the filter press. I wore it when I loaded sulfuric acid gel into the mixers (and I have the acid burn scars to prove it) and it took everything I threw at it without missing a beat. It even kept good time. This watch has taken everything I threw at it from the day I bought it and just keeps going. It‚Äôs not pretty, no. But it is cheap, reliable and tough. It‚Äôs a medium size watch, so it doesn‚Äôt take up much real estate on your wrist and it‚Äôs so light you barely feel as if you have it on. It‚Äôs water-resistant enough for everyday use - no need to worry about getting caught out in the rain. You can even shower with it on, but I‚Äôd probably draw the line at scuba diving. For roughly $10, it‚Äôs pretty tough to beat for someone looking for practical timekeeping, and who isn‚Äôt concerned with the latest fashion.

title: Great Watch with a Classic Design
text:
I had been looking for a relatively cheap digital watch, preferably from Casio, as a simple watch to start the New Year off with. When I searched "casio digital watch" this was about the second product listing, so I knew it had to be a decent watch. I had worn it for a day or two and have since replaced it with the [insert link here]. Here is my review of the Casio F91W-1 and an explanation of why I replaced it.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Design & Build:
For just over $10, this Casio has great build quality and a cool retro design. In fact, the Casio F91W has been produced since 1991 and even has its own Wikipedia (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Casio_F-91W) page! The design of the Casio is simple and classic and is probably one of the reasons why this watch is still successful after 25 years! The watch is very thin, - only 8 millimeters - especially for a digital watch, which is about the same thickness as an iPhone 5. The watch face is made of plastic and is not recessed into the body, meaning that while it is flush with the casing it can be scratched easily. The casing of the watch is made of resin which is pretty standard in most digital watches. The band is also made of resin and is comfortable enough for a $10 watch. One complaint that I have about the watches build quality is the material of which the band buckle is made of. The band buckle is made of ordinary black plastic which I can see breaking in a year or two. While I can't vouch for the longevity of this watch, I can almost confidently say that that plastic buckle will be the first part to break. Other than that, the watch features nice easy-to-press buttons which stick out from the watch a millimeter or two. The buttons are very easy to press, which can be both a good thing and a bad thing as they might be pressed accidentally. The top left button activates the display light which is very weak and only lights up from one side of the display, meaning that the left part of the display is kind of bright while the further you get to the right side of the display the light dims drastically. This seems like one of the areas Casio had to cut corners with in order to cut the cost, however, it is only a minor complaint with a $10 watch. The light shines a green light and only turns on while the button is depressed, which is kind of annoying. Digital watches I have owned in the past stayed on for a few seconds, but again, this is only a minor complaint with a $10 watch. Finally, the Casio features water RESISTANCE, not waterproofing, therefore I wouldn't go swimming with it, however, other users have reported diving with it so the decision is ultimately up to you. Overall, the Casio F91W features a simple and timeless design, as well as pretty good build quality for $10. The display light has some issues and the watch is only water resistant, but these things don't matter too much in a $10 watch.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Fit:
I have around a 6-inch wrist and this watch fit great. I used a hole more towards the end of the band away from the case and it fit comfortably while not being too loose. The watch is very light and once it is on you almost forget it is there. The case is also thin and doesn't add much bulk to your arm. For me, the watch face was a good size proportionate to my wrist. It might have been a little small for my liking but it definitely didn't get in the way. Overall, I am happy with how the F91W fit on my wrist.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Overall:
This watch is a great watch for the price. While I can't vouch for the longevity of this watch, I can say that it features a great design and decent build quality, as well as a good and comfortable fit (at least for my wrists). To conclude, if you have a bit over $10 to spend on a digital watch, you really can't go wrong with the Casio F91W.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Pros:
- Classic simple design
- Decent build quality
- Comfortable
- Thin and light
- Easy-to-press buttons
- Good fit for me
- Accurate time-keeping (Casio claims that the watch is accurate to ¬±30 seconds per month due to the quartz movement of the watch)

Cons:
- Weak plastic band buckle
- Easily scratched plastic face
- Weak and poorly designed display light
- Buttons may get accidentally pressed
- Only water resistant
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Why I Replaced it:
Even though the Casio F91W is a great watch for the money, I decided I wanted something a bit nicer, even if it meant spending a little bit more money. After browsing Amazon for other Casio watches, I came across the [[ASIN:B000AR7S3A G-Shock G100-BV Men's Black Resin Sport Watch]]. The reason why I replaced the F91W isn't because it isn't a good watch, instead, I replaced it because I wanted something a little nicer with a more rugged design. To conclude, I replaced the F91W not because it wasn't good, but because of personal preference.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
If you found this review helpful I would appreciate it if you clicked the "helpful" button below this review. Thanks!

title: Much like in the age of early man
text: In this day and age ‚Äògreatness‚Äô is a term used too often and too frequently, to truly achieve greatness one must bring things back to first principles. Much like in the age of early man, the importance of measuring the passing of time, the arc of the sun and moon across the sky and the changing of seasons has been core to surviving, thriving and dominating, and, in the F91-W we have the essence of the 200,000 year journey mankind has made. When man‚Äôs time on earth has passed, the F91-W will remain, keeping time in dutiful simplicity, abiding by its key tenets of dependability, timelessness and quartz precision. Other watches may come and go and, like the trappings of youth, you might be tempted to look to the glitz and shine of a gold Rolex. For this affliction I‚Äôd recommend the F-91WM-9ACF Casio Men's 'Classic' Quartz Metal and Resin Casual Watch, color: gold. Once the F91-W is on your wrist you will notice the subtle but definite shift of your stress levels, sort of like the soothing feeling of writing on a banana with a ball point pen. Who do I recommend the F91-W for? Well, simply the person who wishes to have a watch that tells the time, especially in dark environs that call for a subtly lit time check instead of the retina-frying, ‚Äòdistant explosion‚Äô light flare of an iPhone screen. Imagine being able to time check the remaining run time of a big screen movie without lighting up the entire theatre? Imagine never having to worry about charging a device you carry with you every single day? Imagine being able to take that device with you even into the shower? Imagine that, even if you break it (which is difficult to do), you need not fear the cost of the loss, nor the time lost trying to navigate an appointment with the Apple Store to fix the ‚Äògorilla glass‚Äô (which let‚Äôs face it should be re-named ‚Äòdelicate flamingo‚Äô glass). Imagine that nobody will even notice you are wearing a watch or even consider mugging you for it and imagine that you can get all this for the princely sum of $10.35 (at time of writing). Well, imagine no more because, in the words of famed 2005 Sydney Swans Premiership Coach Paul Roos, ‚ÄúHERE IT IS!‚Äù.

title: Thin, looks good, and was great for Burning Man
text:
Glad I decided to look online for these, as they were $20 at Target and only ~$10 here. I love Casio's line of cheap, vintage/minimalistic, and compact watches. There are a lot of watches I like, but they are always ridiculously large and dwarf my already small hands.

I wore this to Burning Man for the alarm function. It worked perfectly- it woke me up, was accurate, and didn't break or scratch from the sand either. The light is a little dim, but it worked, and if you had a headlamp it didn't matter anyway. It's easy to use, and because it was plastic it didn't get all gnarly from my sweat, sand, and sunscreen. Easy to clean off and worked perfectly for a week of harsh conditions.

title: My favorite watch
text:
This watch is almost perfect. It is thin, comfortable, legible, accurate, durable, and stylish.

It measures 9mm thick, which looks bigger on a ruler, but feels great on your wrist and is lighter than most other watches.

The problems were that it did not ship with the box pictured; it came in a plastic bag in an envelope, and that the light on it only illuminates from one side, casting an dim and uneven light. For this reason, I think that the [[ASIN:B000GB1RAU Casio Men's F105W-1A Illuminator Digital Watch]] is a better choice; it is the exact same, except it has a much better and more useful light and costs only $3 more. Sadly, it's too late for me, since i've already bought this watch, but once I lose this one (which I'm sure I will before it ever breaks or runs out of batteries), I will definitely buy the other!

Also, the button on the right side of the watch changes the clock from 12hr to 24hr in it's normal mode. Sometimes, when my wrist is bent, it gets pressed unintentionally. This isn't that much of a problem, but I don't think it needs to be that easy to change the time mode.

One last note: be best viewing angle for this watch is around 60 degrees. There's a bit of unclarity if you look at it straight on at 90 degrees or if you slant it too low. This may or may not be a problem for you, depending on your own personal habits, but I think it'd be better if there were wider viewing angles.

title: This is a watch that can cast shadows to your wrist watch collection.
text:
This is a watch that can cast shadows to your wrist watch collection.
I bought it in Argentina. So you wont find the "verified purchase" sign on this review. But I guess these pieces are all of the same sort. Mine was made in Thailand. I adquired it for the gym, but I cant get if off my wrist. I like diver watches, I own a Seiko skx007, an Orient ray blue, even an Omega Seamaster. But the de F91w gets most of my wrist time and I think I know why:
-It is light as a feather. Being used to diver watches as I mentioned, wearing a light watch is very comfy.
-It is very thin. Not obstrusive at all.
-It is very accurate. It wins about one second every 10 days so it keeps time pretty accurately. If you have it on it goes faster, if you dont, goes a bit slower (body temperature). But you can always zero it up (back) if it is between 1 and 29 seconds o (forward) if it is between 31 and 59 seconds. So if you dont let it go further or backward more than 29 seconds you can adjust it just by pressing the right button on *adjust* mode.
-Its dial is very clear. Contrasty. You can see it at every angle.
-The watch is small *but* what I realize is that being a small watch it is not important as far as the *digits* are not small. Which is what tells you the time.
-Night light is dim but enough to show you the time at dark. I gess more potent light compromise the duration of the battery, so I am happy with a longer battery life and light enough to see the time at dark.
-Stop watch is very useful for cooking and other infinite tasks. I use it a lot to time driving times to deliver goods and put it down so I can schedule my delivery shift more accurately.
-It can be used as a morning wake up alarm while travelling but, if you have heavy sleep, you can put it in a mug on the bedside table (see picture) to beep more loudly directing your head. It works.
I think is a watch everyone should try. I was skeptical at the begining but once I bought it I discovered that the watch looks better personally than in pictures. And is very, very comfortable. I hope this review helps to whoever reads it. Greetings from Argentina.

title: Do not buy
text: I have had four or five of this model watch over the last several years.  For each one, one of the four "brackets" that holds one end of the strap pin broke off within a year which made each of the watches useless.  Consequently, I had to buy new ones.  I have kept buying the same watch over and over because I like their functions and they are very inexpensive.  But I guess you get what you pay for.  Secondly, a strap recently broke on my latest watch, so I went to replace the strap with one from one of my previously broken watches and found that the straps appear to be non-replaceable because the strap pins are permanently affixed to the watch rather than being spring loaded as in most watches.  So I wouldn't recommend this watch until they fix the design flaw.

title: Reliable, highly practical, nostalgic even
text: I love this model. I've been using this model of watch for about 20+ years (off and on).  It's not the best looking, or stylish.  I get this model for its practicality.  I first bought this model a decade before the advent of smart-phones, and now all the features of this watch are available on any smartphone.  However, I still buy this model because I appreciate its ruggedness and water-resistance.  I'm very rough with my possessions.  I don't have the most up-to-date smartphone, so I don't have the water-resistance with it.  I usually use this model of watch for about 3-5 years before I have to replace it. Now that I think of it, maybe I buy it now because it reminds me of my more care-free college years, and I'm in my mid-50s now.

title: Great little inexpensive much
text: Great little inexpensive watch. It is very thin, and you hardly know that it‚Äôs there. Exactly what I was looking for.

title: No Brainer Purchase - It covers all of the basics, easy to use, low cost, Casio reliability.
text: For the price, this is the kind of watch that a Minimalist will appreciate....it has the basics - alarm, stop watch, day/date, 24hr time option. I recently picked up a couple of Casio's, I have always owned Casio's - going back to the 80's. I have owned a few expensive pieces as well....automatic movements/ mechanical - Omegas, etc....I always break those and they require expensive servicing.....so I have come to the conclusion that Quartz watches are watches to actually use. Even within the other Casio digital quartz offerings, most people just dont need to spend more really than what this watch offers and represents. Its thin and comfortable...if you are a really big and thick boned person, it may be a problem...but it fits me just fine...and I am not a small person...anyways, I also recently picked up the Casio CA53W ($15) Calc watch and the Casio G Shock GW-M 5600 ($92 range) classic square G Shock in the Solar/ Atomic model. I like all three....but, if I had to pick just one to do all of the basic things....it may be this one - F91W that would be the choice....its something you just dont have to worry about, at under $10.....it has the basic features including a light, the CA53W doesnt have one....downside to that budget watch. The F91 has a very readable face, and an ultra easy to operate interface. As far as durability, it seems like it would hold up to the average daily use of just about anyone...again, if you are ultra hard on a watch....you can buy 2 or 3 of these and just have them on backup....or stash them in other vehicles, at work, in kits, etc. I have seen videos of guys diving at 30 feet/ 10 meters with these little watches....so you could spend $50, $100 or even much more on other Casios, let alone other brands, but what do you need at the end of the day - a watch to tell time day and night, maybe an alarm, maybe a stop watch to time things - meetings, cooking, exercise, etc.....for average practical people who dont want to break the bank and pay for features they dont need....this watch is a smart buy - it does the job. Yeah, I know watch collectors dont think this way, they want style, status, etc....but those reasons for buying a watch are beyond what the watch actually does on a daily basis. And, you have to always be thinking about an expensive watch - banging it on things, scratching the bracelet, scratching the car, not being able to reach into your pocket if its a fat watch....on and on.....just get one of these for $10 or less...and use it....then maybe it will make sense. Lastly, if you travel....you definitely dont want to travel with an expensive watch that you dont want to lose in an airport, have stolen, or generally damage during activities, not to mention, its not smart to stand out in some countries....good way to get robbed, a flashy watch. Buy 2 or 3. As far as a gift.....I think any guy would appreciate one of these as they are very retro cool....and who couldnt use a backup watch even if they already have a more pricey watch, its a watch that grows on you with its simplicity and efficiency.

title: I love this watch!!!
text:
This watch is absolutley AMAZING!!!!!! I had to get this for a medical program so I can count pulse and respiration rate, and I needed a watch to count seconds. I've had this watch for two months now and it works FANTASTICALLY!

First of all, it is REALLY easy to set up and all instructions are included! It is SO handy because it tells you the time in hours, minutes, and seconds! It can also be swtiched from military to AM/PM time with a press of a button! It tells you the day (Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday... etc) and the date (1st, 2nd, 3rd... etc) which is really helpful!! A great added feature!

The watch is very comfortable, and it's easy to adjust!! While going to school, I work at a dog grooming salon and I was so scared to wear this while bathing dogs, because I usually get SOAKED, or at least get water all over my hands/arms. This watch is really durable though! I have gotten it soaked literally every single time I've worked since I've gotten it, and it still looks and works perfectly! I've also dropped this watch a couple times with no damage!

I HIGHLY recommend this watch, its really useful and a GREAT deal for the price!!!

title: Casio F91W-1 Classic Resin Strap Digital Sport Watch -- Impressive!
text:
Just received the watch today -- can't beat it as an add-on for less than $6.00. Watched reviews on you tube and this is an authentic Casio (holding the button near the seconds display for 3 seconds will produce the CASIO name on the screen and holding all three buttons down will display all the symbols that the watch uses). Back of watch says made in Thailand and the front of the buckle says CASIO and the rear says CHINA.
Comes with instructions and warranty. Very easy to set the time, date, and seconds. Very thin and use the third hole on the strap (so it allows me to place one finger between the watch and my wrist. I have other Casio watches (mostly solar atomic g-shocks) that are more expensive, but this watch is much smaller, accurate, and is worth adding to my collection. Should last for years, and if the strap breaks it's easier to replace the watch anyway. It's a classic, so don't hesitate -- buy it!

title: Best bang for the buck
text:
First, this was an impulse purchase. I love watches. Once I saw it and the price tag, I had to have it. For $11 and change (including sales tax), this is the best bang for the buck.

Second, this watch is smaller and slimmer than it appears in photos. But that is actually a positive, as I needed a thin light watch with a stopwatch for the gym anyway. Running is much more comfortable with the F-91W than with a G Shock.

Third, the light (lamp) is pretty much useless. It shines from the left side, and I can barely make out the hour. Forget the minutes, those digits are totally in the dark.

All in all, it does what a $11 digital watch is expected to do. No regrets.

title: Unbelievable value, compares well to the more expensive A158 models.
text:
I probably shouldn't even bother writing this, as there are hundreds of reviews already. I'm a Casio watch collector, so I can't resist. I have the "higher-end" brother of this watch, the A158W. It has the stainless steel band. The function is the same, but this one is much more comfortable, due to the soft and semi-porous resin band, compared to the hair-pulling bracelet. It also has the superior electro-luminescent backlight. (the A158W has a single, dim LED on the side, which brings me back to the 80s, when they had incandescent side lights)

The A158W has a nicer display. The light gray background is smoother. On the F91W, we can see the gray background is kind of grainy and not quite as contrasting with the LCD digits. The A158W looks more dressy though; doesn't make you embarassed to wear it to business casual work.

title: No-nonsense watch
text: I got this for my clinical as I did not want to wear a nicer fossil watch in an ambulance or to a hospital. I actually started wearing this with more regularity. For around 10 bucks you get a water-resistant (Proof as far as I've seen) reliable watch that fits pretty well. I'm a 6'3'' guy and it fits me on the third to last hole if I want it tight or second to last hole if I want it a little looser. It has a LED light which while isn't that bright and doesn't fully illuminate the whole screen - works well enough. Also has an alarm feature, hourly alarm, and a stop watch. Can do 12/24 hour time as well. It's a pretty great watch, and one you wont be afraid of hurting since it's 10 bucks. There's apparently a whole community that mods these too, like adding photo film to give it a negative display. Try it out, for the price of a burrito you wont' be disappointed!

title: World's best watch?
text:
To address some of the negative reviews.

1) There are a lot of fakes of this watch. The genuine watch comes in one color, black, according to the Casio website. Given there's a pink version available on Amazon, apparently they don't know the difference! (See youtube on telling fakes apart.) I bought directly from Amazon, not simply fulfilled, and received the genuine article in a Casio box, with documentation, and warranty papers. If your watch breaks early or is inaccurate, you have a fake. If water killed your watch, it's probably fake. If your watch came in a plastic bag, it's probably fake. If the watch smells like plastic, it's fake.

2) This watch is the perfect size for smaller wrists. If you want a big watch, this is not for you.

3) The resin band is very comfortable. It's waterproof, won't absorb sweat, and it nicely designed. I don't see it breaking anytime soon.

This is a great watch. It stays perfectly accurate for days and days. It's been to the pool and rained on, and it still looks new.

Note: The correct country of origin is Thailand. Amazon incorrectly lists China and sometimes USA.

title: Good watch...poor watch band
text: Don't get me wrong. Casio makes really good watches and sells them at a very low price. This watch, the F91W-1 is a great example of this....HOWEVER....they compromise drastically with the watch band. I have a very average size wrist but am forced to use the second to last hole in the band. By doing so, the keeper which you tuck the "remainder" of the band into is barely able to hold it. It would not cost much, if even a dollar to lengthen the bands on watches like the F91W-1. The F28-W is another one with short-band-itis. Because of the way the band is somewhat integrated into the design of the watch, changing/upgrading bands is not easy to do. Plus, removing and reinstalling the pins which secure the band to the watch is almost sure to damage the plastic tabs they mount in. Trust me, I've done it. One of Casio's best budget-priced watches, in my opinion, is the W201-1AV. Ample band length, shows day/month & date without pushing a button, PLUS a 10-year battery. Casio, please upgrade the bands on the other aforementioned watches among others.

title: Captured by crazy military, Watch keeps Ticking even when my heart stops.
text:
As a middle eastern hipster it's easy for me to find old 80's American and Japanese technology at the local bazar. I spied this gem for a pittance of a chicken and HAD to have it. It was better then finding a fixie hauling PBR!! (If I were allowed to drink) No sooner had I strapped my retro classic to my wrist and checked the time that a black hood closed over my head. At first I hoped it was irony but I was wrong SO WRONG!

I was soon moving in a truck, I could feel sweat beading under the rubber strap of my Casio F91W-1 and knew the timepiece was still attached to my wrist able to tell me how long I'd traveled. Alas I awoke in a haze, as my hands clenched behind me I could not check the time.
I couldn't distinguish the pain of the zip tie cuffs from my Casio F91W-1 smooth rubber strap but soon found my new watch dangling before my face as a man screamed "WHY DO YOU OWN THIS WATCH!?!" "To know what time it is I muttered meekly," I could see it was 1AM, I was missing Adventure Time being broadcast from the United States. "CAN YOU TELL ME WHY 32 OTHER TERRORISTS HERE HAVE THIS SAME WATCH!?!" I searched my brain, 32? That sales man said I had the only one in the country, I wasn't unique anymore? I was going to need a new watch. "They were all lied to by the salesman as well?" I answered still thinking I was being persecuted as a hipster yet again *le sigh. "A wise guy eh? We have ways of making you talk"

I was reluctantly given my watch back, I was told it was so I'd know which way to pray with my Casio F91W-1's compass feature but the man didn't believe that I wasn't religious but that my outfit was indeed chosen for irony. Seriously, robes in a desert, how do you not get that?

I soon heard through the grape vine that I've be transferred to Cuba, Knowing little of the world from my antique text books I thought Cuba was still the Monte Carlo of the American corrupt and looked forward to my pleasant tropical extravaganza.

What I underwent in Cuba was more horrible then `The Situation' trying to roast a Hummer H2 with Rebecca Black Singing Friday in the Front seat (or back) but despite years of agony and much water exposure my Casio F91W-1 still works keeping the time of my innocence alive.

title: Great watch!!! (Just try to ignore its infamous association)
text:
Elegant, accurate, thin watch, and excellent bang for the buck. The optional hourly chime reminds me of my childhood. As another reviewer noted, anyone who complains about this watch doesn't know how good a watch can be for $10. This is one of the few digital watches that is thin enough to not snag on my long sleeve work shirts (and I button them with the looser button). I have this great system: I wear the A158W-1 (same watch but in shiny stainless steel; looks like it's worth $100!) for work or more professional/formal occasions, and this one for casual or sports. For not much more than $20 for the two watches, it's an awesome system for me and I love the modesty, basic functionality, and what I call an "anti-hoity toity" feeling!

Press and hold the right lower button for 5 seconds until it says "Casio" in digital letters to verify it's authentic.

After I purchased it I was reading about it on a Casio collector's website and was disappointed to discover that this watch was worn by the most infamous terrorist of our time (whom I will not name; he can be seen wearing this watch in photos) and has been favored by them. I try to ignore this awful association and just enjoy the watch. Some websites have even suggested that if you wear this watch, you might be suspected as being one, which I find far fetched: http://gizmodo.com/5795554/people-wearing-this-casio-watch-might-be-terrorists So if you're the paranoid type, just put it away or leave it at home when going through airport security.

title: Nothing Fancy - Does The Job.
text:
This watch is nothing fancy. It has a built-in stop watch, light and alarm (in addition to displaying the day of week - Mon, Tue, etc., time, and day - 1st, 2nd, etc.). This watch also has "12/24 Hour" mode so you can see the time in "1pm" or "1300" formats (i.e. "military time").

I typically do not wear a wrist watch but use my cellphone instead. Due to circumstances of a camp I volunteer at, cellphones are not allowed so I needed an inexpensive replacement wrist watch that is nothing fancy (since I don't normally wear a watch and will go back to using the cellphone for time when not at this particular camp).

This watch does the basic functions well. There are only two negatives I would give:

1) the wrist band is a little short. For an adult reasonably muscular male (not sure what what my wrist diameter is), I was able to get the band around my wrist but ended up using the second-to-last hole in the band. Not a big deal but something to be aware of.

2) The light is NOT a "back-light" in that it does NOT light up the back of the watch face. Instead, the light is mounted on the left side of the display face and shines from left to right. This causes you to need to give the display a close look when using the light feature in low / dark ambient lighting.

As I've noted, I was looking for a BASIC / inexpensive watch and this one, even with the above two negatives, fits the bill nicely. Would I buy this again if I were in the market - yes, I would.

title: Around the House Watch
text:
So, I like to wear a watch around the house and when I sleep. I have a decent sized watch collection, but few things I consider to be my home utility watch. I wanted to add to that collection, so that was the mindset I had for this piece. This piece has a lot of history, which is cool, and it serves the primary function of telling time fine. However, there is some utility it lacks, and in all honesty I would tell you to pass on this watch. So hear is what I can say:
Intended Use: Around the house utility with need for in the dark functionality.
That said it fared ok at this. It is pretty small, but very clear to read. It is a very small thin watch, even on my skinny wrists, but still is able to be read in a lit room or outside easily. I do enjoy that I do not notice it, which makes it easier for doing tasks without snagging it or having it impede mobility.
The negative is that this light is the worst I have ever had on a watch. You get the hour and that is about it. This really killed the use for me as I like to be able to check the time quickly at night without the use of my phone.
Also, I use my watches for cooking, and without a countdown timer, there goes another aspect of functionality I would like. Remember it has a stopwatch, but no countdown timer.

My recommendation would be to spend an extra ten bucks and get the really cool Casio World Time that gives you a better light, timer, stopwatch, and different time zones for travel. It is also a lot bigger and easier to read at night. I greatly prefer that watch.

This watch however does do a killer job of telling you the time and date, and if you are looking for something with the least amount of wrist-presence while telling you the time effectively then this is a great watch. If you want much more out of it, there is a lot better for not a lot more money.

So when operating the watch in the dark you have to memorize how to do things like set an alarm, as the light button changes settings and the light does not stay on when you press it. So you have to press it once to see what screen you are on, then press the other buttons in the right combination to set the correct time for something like an alarm.

title: Plain and Comfortable Design but DREADFUL LED Light
text:
I must say before I begin this review: I was extremely ambivalent as to whether this watch is a 3 or 4 star product.

As soon as I received this watch, I immediately thought it was too small, which may or may not be a good thing depending on you. I've been using my brother's G-Shock for quite a while now, and it's uncomfortable (despite all of the hype) and way too bulky! So, because of how this picture depicted the size (where the batteries go), I bought this watch. Also, the G-Shock and many other expensive watches have many designs at the sides of the back as opposed to this watch's straight round design, which makes it ergonomic. In addition, this watch is REALLY light, which again, can be good or bad. But here comes my major gripe. This watch's lighting aspect is so bad that I wouldn't even wear it if I got paid $15 to (which funnily is what happened because when I tried to refund it, Amazon politely accepted my refund AND surprised me by saying I can keep the watch too)!

The light:
First of all, the button for the light on this watch is so tiny which may make it hard to find for some people and also to push. But if you do manage to push the button, the light only stays on as long as you push it, and to completely kill the entire glory of the watch, the light is horrendous! I was so disappointed. Seriously, this light is so bad and only barely covers the left side of the watch. What was Casio thinking?!

I would also like to add that the design of this watch is so simple and kind of boring, but once again...it's so comfortable as opposed to other bulky watches! And because of the thinness, it's much easier to slide on tight men (or women's) clothing such as dress shirts, etc. I would recommend this watch if you are willing to ignore the poorly-designed lighting portion and the ordinary look.

*Unrelated*
After analyzing carefully a few other inexpensive watches, I came across Casio Men's W735H-1AVCF Super Illuminator Black Watch. This watch seems really good but also uncomfortable due to the similar strap design of the G-Shock. But what makes elevated it is the huge "Light" button, which I find very important and the extremely useful vibrating alarm since I am a very forgetful person, and sometimes I may be listening to something and won't hear my watch's alarm.

Also, Casio Men's WV58A-1AVCR Waveceptor Atomic Digital Watch:
Has a similar designed strap (comfortable), which, as mentioned before, is what makes the Casio F91W-1 Classic Resin Strap Digital Sport Watch good! It also has EL lighting, which is far superior to LED lighting I think. Furthermore, the button for the light is medium-sized and is at the right side of the watch, which is so-so (i.e. workable).

With a picky and frugal personality like mine, it's extremely difficult to find a perfect, inexpensive watch ($15-$25).

text:
Probably the best watch I've ever owned. To be frank however, its ugly. Its very functional however. No real frills, you can easily tell the time, the day, and the day of the month. It has a 12/24hr. it has a Alarm feature, with the ability the beep at every hour, or an alarm at a time whenever you want. Then the next feature is the stopwatch featuring lap times. I'm not sure how this works but I never needed to time things.

It is ugly though. Its black, but the face of the casio is ugly. My biggest complaint of it. If one could easily get rid of all of the stuff on the face of the watch, it would look very nice.

title: An amazing watch for a great value!
text: This is the first watch I've ever bought. Well sort of. I've been waiting on my real first watch(Casio G-shock,Gorillaz Ltd. Ed) in the mail but it's been taking way longer than expected so I picked this up as a temporary replacement until that gets here but this little 12 dollar watch has impressed me so much that I had to come rave about it! This is not only a classic and sharp looking watch with its square design but is also super easy to read from all angles, is so light you can barely tell it's on your wrist and the resin makes the body virtually indestructible.  I have barely scratched the face after wearing it every day for a week as a part time maintenance worker at a hotel. It's been soaked and even submerged in a couple inches of water(which it is not really meant to be) and still keeps going! I seriously love this thing! My only problem is the buttons are a lil stiff and hard to push somewhat (which is ok cuz they dont get accidentally pushed either) and the light isnt that great but it DOES work fine. I just wish the light was a tiny bit brighter. Neither of these are very big deals, this watch is an amazing design by Mr. Ryusuke Moriai and I will definitely be collecting all the color variants in the future. title: Great Watch
text:
This watch is slim and fits very comfortably. It's a nice throwback to a classic 80s style. The button mapping is very simple to learn, and I picked up on how to use the watch in just a minute or so. Many people comment on how much they love the watch and remember the good days of watches like it.

My only complaint is in regards to setting the alarm. I often do this once in bed and the lights are out. However, the light button is the one that lets you change fields, thus making it impossible to set in the dark. Just turn on a lamp and everything is fine. Not really a big deal.

Alarm is nice and loud. Display is simple to read indoors and outdoors. For the price it'd be hard to find a better watch.

title: Great Watch
text:
This is a great watch, it gives you everything you need, and nothing else. I mean, why would you need a watch that tells you the time, and has 36 alarms, and tells you where the moon is in the sky?

The watch is very light-weight, and very unnoticeable. You could slap it on, and forget it was even on. The lightness comes at a small cost due to the durability of the strap, its mostly fine, but the points where it attaches to the watch, seem a little thin, or "could be thicker".

The watch keeps a good time, losing maybe 20 seconds every 4 months or so? Which is fine, since its pretty simple to re-adjust the time.

The watch is really cheap, sorta like a disposable watch, you won't worry if you lose it since its so easy to replace, and it'll last you a fourth of a life time if you treat it right.

Though its a reliable watch, its very few bells and whistles like the light, is poorer quality, but gets the job done. Its a simple, LED or such on the left of the watch, but it gets straight to the point, it lets you see what time it is at night, or in the dark. Unless you fancy the entire thing lighting up like a flashlight then you'll be fine.

It says its water resistance, but I wouldn't trust it.

Overall, buy it. Unless you are expecting a solid gold 24k watch with diamond studded numbers, and it tells you when all the planets align.

title: still love them, but mostly I just want a watch ...
text:
I‚Äôm over big, bulky watches. I‚Äôve got my Suunto and a couple G-Shock watches. I still wear them, still love them, but mostly I just want a watch that keeps nice, precise time, doesn‚Äôt stand out from my wrist 3/4 inch and hopefully looks juuuust a little dorky. I‚Äôm also cheap. Waterproofness is important to me. I work a desk job. I commute by bus or train- watches help with that. I like to go on a run a couple times a week and wear a watch. I don‚Äôt sleep or shower with my watch on unless I‚Äôm camping or in a hotel. I like digital over analog because I kind of like to know exactly what time I think it is and I only ever estimate when I‚Äôm reading an analog watch because I‚Äôm lazy. Also, when I‚Äôm in a meeting or I‚Äôve been pinned-down by someone I don‚Äôt want to talk to and I want to know if this really is taking forever or if my perception of the passage of time is just being warped- it‚Äôs easier to sneak a peek at a digital watch and get a precise read. I realized a few months ago that I really am just as happy wearing a $15 Casio as I am with my $250 Suunto and that most days I don‚Äôt need to know the barometric pressure. Some days, yes. Most days, no. But I like having a variety of watches (including the Suunto, which is fabulous). And I like to choose which watch to wear each morning. That‚Äôs fun for me. Recently I got on Amazon and ordered a bunch of new cheap Casio watches. I got four new watches for $52. I think Timex‚Äôs are over-priced. That‚Äôs how cheap I am.

Casio W-800HAV ($20-ish) Digital Black. My eight-year old son and I each got one of these watches for Christmas 2016. We both love it. We both have other watches but wear this one the most. It has a fairly low profile- doesn‚Äôt catch on pockets or shirt sleeves. I love the light- it looks stupid, like piddly. But it actually lights the face well. I go jogging at night sometimes. The light works well enough for me to see how slow I am even while I‚Äôm bouncing down the road. And it‚Äôs got ‚ÄúDual Display‚Äù. I don‚Äôt know what else to call that. It shows the time on one part of the screen and at the same time it show the stopwatch numbers. Nice to keep track of both. Or, If I‚Äôm out and about, I‚Äôll set a stopwatch when the train goes by because I know that the train comes by every 15 minutes. So I can see when I‚Äôm coming up on another 15-minute mark and also see the time on the sub-display.

Casio F-201WA ($10.47) Digital Black. Comfortable. Lightweight. Easiest buttons to push. Good light. I like that it has countdown timer and lots of alarms. I miss being able to see the time when it‚Äôs in stopwatch mode like I can with the W-800HAV and the WV-200A.

Casio WV-200A ($40-ish) Waceceptor Digital Black with chrome and red. Looks good. Like the steel case. Good protection for the glass. Relatively heavy. A liiiiitle too thick. Really nice buttons. Great electro-luminescent light. This one is the only watch of the group that you can set it so it doesn‚Äôt beep every time you push a button. I really like being able to turn the beep off. Sometimes I like to set a stopwatch in a meeting so I can see how long somebody is going on with some bullsh*t. Strangely, timing somebody‚Äôs bullsh*t is a nice distraction from the bullsh*t. But I don‚Äôt like my watch to beep when I‚Äôm doing pushing buttons. ‚ÄúDual display‚Äù- you can still see what time it is when you‚Äôre in other modes. Countdown timer is nice and many of my other watches don‚Äôt have one. I don‚Äôt give it extra points for the whole Wave Ceptor thing. Doesn‚Äôt add any value for me and it kinda sucks battery. This watch has been on my wrist for a full day of snorkelling and handled it beautifully. I live in a land-locked state, so when I get to the ocean, I‚Äôm in the water ALL DAY LONG. I can‚Äôt dive deeper than maybe 20 feet, so it‚Äôs not a serious test for a watch that says it‚Äôs good to 200m. But if you‚Äôre diving to 200m and time is critical, you‚Äôre going to spring for something more than a $40 Casio. (I love you, Casio).

Casio HDA-600 ($14.79) Black Analog. Not the most comfortable. Kinda squeezes my wrist from bone to bone or flops around a bit. I dunno, it just fits weird. YMMV. Love the face protector. Can‚Äôt wait until it starts to look a little banged up. Glowy dots on the hands aren‚Äôt really impressive. Date window works perfectly. Looks tough but it‚Äôs probably not. I like it a lot.

Casio MQ24-7B2 ($14-something) White-faced Analog. Incredibly light. Truly forget that you‚Äôre wearing it. Easy to read. No date window. No lumi. Nice, simple and never catches your sleeve in a dress shirt. Yes, I‚Äôm fancy. Some people are smart enough to read an analog watch that doesn‚Äôt have numbers on it- just dots. I‚Äôm not one of those people. I screw it up enough when there‚Äôs numbers. This has numbers. I like numbers. Haven‚Äôt tested this one for waterproofyness. Casio only says it‚Äôs water resistant. I hardly ever do underwater demolitions anymore.

Casio A168W-1 ($16.15) Stainless Digital. I love / hate this watch. I don‚Äôt know if Casio was really trying to make a watch that looks fancy but it‚Äôs really a dork-bomb, or if they we‚Äôre going for dork-bomb as their aim. Either way. This watch is a stunning success. I think this watch is the pinnacle of nerd-swank. 1980‚Äôs wannabe stockbroker, cool old guy who doesn‚Äôt give a sh*t, little bit of silver under the sleeve to catch someone‚Äôs eye- oh wait it‚Äôs a friggin Casio digital. I mean, it‚Äôs chrome-plated PLASTIC for crying out loud. How awesome is that? I love all of that. Love it. It‚Äôs got the Illuminator light, which works great. Clock, date, stopwatch and alarm. No countdown timer. The metal band is not comfortable. It‚Äôs got edges and it pulls on my arm fur. Clasp works great and it‚Äôs wicked-easy to adjust. Slips under a dress shirt easily. Again: super-dorky. Makes me smile every time I put it on. Then wince when it pulls the fur.

Casio F91W-1 ($11.35) Black Digital. I like this watch a lot. It‚Äôs super thin. Very lightweight. The light looks stupid but it works well. The buttons are easy to hit. It ranks pretty high on the ‚ÄòDork‚Äô scale. People recognize it. Hold that one button down and it says CASIo. It‚Äôs great. Proud to say I‚Äôve never worn this watch along with flannel and a beanie. Never.

title: A trustworthy friend.
text:
This watch is a classic. It won't ever go out of style for one reason, it does what it's supposed to and it does it well. Nothing more, nothing less.

Easy - It's digital so you look down and you know what time it is. Seems silly but being able to quickly read the time is nice. Programming it is a cinch. There are only three buttons so even if the buttons weren't labeled (which they are) it's not hard to figure out. There are only basic functions like alarm, time, date, and stopwatch. That's it. You don't have to go through a million different options and weird combinations of button presses.

Durable - I wore it on a camping trip to Zion and Bryce Canyon. It survived rocks, dust, water, mud, sun, and my recklessness. There's hardly a scratch on it and the watch face is still immaculate.

Comfortable - It's very light and compact. I can wear it all day and not notice it. My wrists are on the smaller side so the size of the watch face suits me well. It's not overbearing like a lot of other watches for men. By the way, this is fine as a unisex watch. Much respect to all people who wear this watch, men or women. You get extra points in my book.

Reliable - The battery will last. Time-telling is pretty accurate. Oddly durable. Simple. You won't mind wearing it. Also, really cheap. There's a reason these watches haven't changed. You'll have the peace of mind of knowing you can lose it and abuse it, and easily and inexpensively replace it. No need to baby it or worry about it.

It seems odd to buy a watch when everyone uses cellphones for everything but once you start wearing a watch you really are more observant of time. It truly does keep you cognizant. This item belongs in the category of things like Nokia phones, Koss Porta-pros, IBM mechanical keyboards, and old Swingline staplers. They just simply work. Form and function going hand in hand. So you could spend money on a restaurant burger, a bottle of wine, a movie ticket, a drink at a bar or... you could buy this watch which will last you the next 20 years. You could also keep browsing trying to find the perfect watch but think of all the time you might be wasting.

If you want to scream the word "practical" then this timeless timepiece is for you.

title: Not fancy, simple, durable, it works, light could be better.
text:
This is my third time buying this watch, everytime I've had to replace it... it's because I've let someone borrow it for whatver purpose adn they've lost it.

There's not much to say about this watch, it's durable, it's waterproof, sorry, water RESISTANT, which just means that you can't take this watch diving, but for everything else in your life, it's fine. Cooking, showering, swimming, beach, surfing, etc. This watch can handle it, but diving is a no go.

It's easy to set an alarm, use the stop-watch, set the time, etc. It's a simple watch, it's straightforward. I like it for it's smaller and slimmer profile, and the rubber band.

CONS:
- The backlight on the watch could better. The watch has a light but the light only comes from the leftside of the screen, it's bright enough to illuminate the entire watch face but you can clearly tell the light only comes from the left, because part of the right side of the watchface is still somewhat dim even while the backlight is on.
- It'd be nice to have a dedicated light button. Sometimes I need to ajdust the time, or check the stopwatch, or shut off an alarm in the dark, but it's not possible here, because the light button is the selection button, it changes your current setting selection, so if you want to add an hour to adjust for daylights savings, you can't do it in the dark, because everytime you get your watch to the hours setting, if you push the light button, it will change to the date-settings, so you'll suddenly be forced to adjust the date. I know the slightly more expensive version of this watch has 4 buttons which gets rid of this problem, so if this is going to be ahuge problem for you, spring for 4 buttons intead of 3. It's not that big of a deal for me, but just something you might want to be aware of.

title: If you're looking for a wristwatch daily driver...
text:
At one point in time, I tried to be one of the few smartwatch believers. I thought that the future lied with wearable technology, and that smartwatches were signs of the future in the present. I wore a Pebble with pride and loved it dearly, then I made the jump to a gorgeous, Android Wear Moto 360. I adored the thing for about three months, before growing tired of the clunky software, hard to use interface, and the user experience that just made it easier to pull out my phone and complete what I wanted. For a category of product based around getting you to interact with your wrist as a quicker, easier alternative to pulling out your phone, it seemed all I did was just that - and I got sick of it.
So, after not wearing it for a month, I ordered this Casio watch and took my Moto 360 to the pawnshop for fifteen dollars. When this came in and I put it on for the first time, I was struck with the revelation that there was no other way - there was no need for anything more complex on my wrist and in my life than this classic piece of tech.
I wear it day in and day out, except for showering. It is resilient, water resistant enough to handle natural, day to day splashes and accidents, easy to use and it always works. I can always count on the back light in a dark room, I can always count on it to beep with every hour, if I desire an alarm or stopwatch I can find it with only a few clicks of it's simple UI - it is simply reliable. It also looks good enough with nearly every outfit I've worn, being both casual enough and being small and discreet enough to look fine with dressier outfits.
I love this thing. I've tried mechanical watches, and I've tried the smartwatches, and sure - they all have their purposes. But if you're looking for your daily driver of wrist wear, look no further: this little thing will fulfill all your time telling needs... and just enough more.

title: Absolute best value of an everyday workhorse of a watch.
text:
It's not fancy. It doesn't have all the bells and whistles. It's not waterproof. It doesn't have a bright LCD backlight to illuminate the face in the dead of night.
Instead what it will do is accurately tell you the time, wake you up reliably in the morning, have probably the lowest weight of any decent wristwatch available, and have a classic minimalist aesthetic which will make those who see it envious, all while setting you back a grand total of 11 usd.
Dollar for dollar, this is hands-down the best watch I've ever owned. It's timeless (pun definitely intended).

title: Great watch!
text:
I love this watch. What I love most about this watch is the compact light-weight feel of it. It is simple to use and has decent functions. I use this watch for everyday use, including hiking/camping.

When I use it for everyday life here in Southern California, it does exactly what I want it to do; tell me time. Not much more you can ask for.

When I take it hiking/camping, I notice some problems. First is that the light button sucks. It is located poorly on the top left corner and the light it gives off is pretty crappy. I can read the time, but it could display the time better. Also the light only stays on while pushing on the button; I'd prefer the watch to light up for a few sec after pushing the button once. The second problem is that there is condensation within the screen in hot or cold weather. Idk what it is exactly, but a somewhat thick layer of water solidifies under the screen in certain temperatures and conditions. Reading the time because very difficult when this occurs. The screen eventually clears up and looks good again when conditions get better, but it shouldn't happen at all. I wonder about the water-resistance capabilities of this watch. I'm afraid to even shower with it on. It gets an A for scratch-resistance however. I've brushed against trees, bushes, etc and the screen still looks great.

Overall it's a great introductory watch for a low price of 11$. It has been very useful to me and I'm glad I bought it. If this watch was 15$+ though, I don't think I would buy it again; for 10$ I would. I will however be upgrading to a more expensive watch next time for a truly water-tight seal (very important to me because I go to lakes, rivers, and streams a lot).

title: BOY this thing takes paintballs like a champ
text:
I love this watch, I've worn this for, I don't know maybe four years, and it's still ticking. I've worn it in rainy weather, I've worn it while playing paintball and perhaps not taking direct hits but it definitely had paint and dirt and grime on it.

I bought three and gave two away as gifts, and both of those people lost them immediately. That is painful, knowing I could have given those watches to people who actually wouldn't have lost them.

For how cheap this watch was, and all him and I have been through, you owe it to yourself.

However, the light is really bad. It's like an actual light bulb, not the screen lighting up. Yes I can see the time but it's not good. I lose maybe one second every week/week and a half so you don't have to worry about accurate time. Very simple to adjust the time, as there are only three buttons on this watch. One button is the light, one button switches between the 12 hour and 24 hour clock, and the third button cycles you through which part of the watch you want to adjust and you just hit the second button to adjust it up or down, depending on the situation.
Very slim; I have skinny wrists and it fits me perfectly so if you have beefier wrists you might want to find a larger model. It's thin so it doesn't mess with my shirts or hamper me from reaching into a pocket or whatever.
Watch might clash with your outfit if you want to dress up for an event or business or work, but any other sort of situation who cares what you wear on your wrist fellow Kings, Queens, and Emperors.

When the battery finally dies, I think I'll replace the battery rather than buy a new watch.

The only negative I can think of on this watch is that the backlight is pretty much useless. I lights from one side and doesn't illuminate the full length of the display. With that said this is my daily go to watch. simple, comfortable and certainly not a fashion statement, unless you are looking for the simple black look. I it is a comfortable watch to wear. slim, both in width and in thickness. Not a large bulky watch. Standard LED display which is easy to read(in the daylight), with crisp characters.
It displays the time in hours, minutes, and seconds. I have never understood why they always show the seconds on these digital watches. I don't need it and wish that it was an option that could be turned on or off. I understand that some people want, need, it but I don't. It also show the day and date but not the month. If you are looking for an inexpensive go to digital watch it is almost impossible to go wrong with this one. If the light issue bothers you, I recommend the Casio F-105. title: Simple, reliable, inexpensive
text: This is probably the third of these watches I have purchased for my 10 year old son -- he either loses them or breaks them.  The watch is durable (but nothing will survive my son's roughness).  The watch's small size and light weight make it easy to wear -- you forget that you are wearing it.  It has simple, easy to use controls and does not have a lot of bells and whistles.  The light works well when the watch is new, but over time as the battery runs down, the light is not very effective at seeing the time in the dark.  As long as you do not overuse the light, the battery seems to last a long time (and probably will outlive the watch if you are rough with it).  The best part is that if the watch gets beaten up, it is so inexpensive that you can just order another one.  If the strap breaks (it's just plastic after all), it might make more sense to order a new watch than to replace the strap (unless you find a strap that is under $10).

title: I don't always get waterboarded but when I do I wear a Casio F91W-1
text:
As you're aware, the Casio F91W-1 is the watch of choice for terrorists. Now, I'm not a terrorist but one look at this fine timepiece alerts the CIA to my presence and they always want to know more about it, where I got it from, who my friends are, and about my future plans. Casio humbly does not claim this watch is waterproof yet never once has a display fogged on me.

Whether you're headed to the office, out for the weekend or are on a SECRET airliner flying around the world to an undisclosed location, I recommend the Casio F91W-1.

As an added bonus, if you can get your hand into the bag over your head, the display lights up so you'll always know the time.

title: Exactly what I wanted
text: This is a watch. There are no unnecessary bells and whistles; it is just a watch. The watch will tell time and has an alarm. This is my first watch, so I can't compare it to other watches, but it is nice and simple (and durable), easy to use, and can go with a variety of different outfits. My only complaint is that the light is terrible. If you use the light, it is not very bright, and emits only from the left edge of the display, which gives it a strange look. In many cases the light actually makes the watch harder to read because of the way it shines onto the plastic above the display -- a minor annoyance, but one which can be overlooked since the light will work well enough in complete (or near complete) darkness (which, I guess, is what really matters). I would recommend this watch to anyone looking for a cheap and reliable timepiece.

title: My girlfriend's favorite in her Casio collection!
text:
I recently purchased a pink Casio watch for my girlfriend as a gift and she absolutely loves it! She has always been a fan of Casio watches and appreciate the vintage feeling they give off.

The pink color of this watch is so cute and adds a fun pop of color to her wardrobe. The watch is well-built and has a very solid feel to it. She finds it very comfortable to wear and also easy to read. The watch features a stopwatch and alarm, which are functionalities she finds really useful.

She has received many compliments on the watch since she started wearing it and I'm happy to see her enjoying it so much. I highly recommend this particular pink Casio watch for anyone looking for a stylish and functional timepiece.

title: Every person should have one
text:
This is a great watch!

Pros:

It does what a watch was design to do, to tell time. It is not one of those fancy digital watch that will tell the altimeter or distance above sea level. It keep track of time, and tell the date, that's it, the essential thing a watch design to do. The digital display can be change between 12 and 24 hour display. It also display the day of the week and seconds. To calibrate it, simply press one of the button until the screen flash. The battery is extremely durable, it will last more than 10 year.

Cons:

The screen of the watch can be scratch easily. If you are a outdoor person, this watch will get scratch some how. I have used this watch for two years, then the strap start to crack, eventually it breaks. The plastic wrist strap is not design to last long, it will not stand strong heat, so do not leave this watch in the car during summer season. Unfortunately, the strap cost almost as much as the watch. So it will be easier to buy a new one, instead of replacing the strap.

Final Thoughts:

The batter will long a really really long time, but It doesn't matter how long the battery will last, the wrist strap will fail first. So you will end up spending $10 every couple years if you want to continue to wear this watch on your hand.

title: Great Affordable Watch - Not a waste of $11.49
text:
(SKIP TO END FOR QUICK VERDICT WITH LESS DETAIL)
DETAILED ANALYSIS: This watch is great if you need a simple yet solid digital watch to keep track of overall time. If you have an active lifestyle and are looking for an affordable watch to pick up, then I would highly recommend it. I am personally satisfied with the ergonomics, and the general build seems sturdy and well constructed. The water resistance also seems to be satisfactory. If I had to point out any doubts in the build of this watch, the only questionable part is the band. The feel of the band does not feel like that of a band made from premium material. So far, the watch is still fully intact and functioning and the band seems like it can sustain under fairly tough circumstances, however, I believe the best way to upgrade this watch would be to interchange the band. Another aspect that needs room for improvement is the backlight. The back light barely lights up half of the watch interface (see photos for example), and it's actually very disappointing. If you are going to depend highly on this watch in the dark, I probably wouldn't recommend it. Lastly, the watch overall looks slightly small compared to

PROS:
Affordable - low risk investment for budget minded
Utility - very useful if you care more about uses than looks
Simplicity - easy to use and control
Sturdy - can withstand most circumstances

CONS:
Cheap Band - the band 'feels' cheap
Terrible Backlight - light does not provide sufficient visibility in the dark
Aesthetics - kinda looks small on wrist; it's not ugly, it just doesn't look nice lol

title: A Good Sports Watch, but the nightlight is inadequate and there is no timer.
text:
I bought this watch to replace a 32 year old Casio. After doing my research, I bought the Ironman Classic 30 and a Casio F91W.
The Ironman is a better watch, but The price and ruggedness of the Casio can‚Äôt be beat.

First, I need to put this review in context. I am a reasonably, if not very active, forty-something. I am fit, but I have a 40 year old‚Äôs eyes and sensibilities. I use this watch primarily Just to tell time at the gym, hiking, biking or maybe swimming. I have some secondary use for it as a timer or stopwatch, but that is about it.

As you might have guessed, I am a bit of a watch minimalist, so I was happy with the size of the watch. However, I am realizing that a 35mm watch may not be optimal for a 40 year old‚Äôs eyes. To be clear I think the watch is perfectly legible/ readable, but the larger face of the Ironman is easier to read and better for older eyes.

Personally I find the controls for the watch intuitive and easier to use (other than the smaller buttons) than the Ironman, but that is coming from a guy who used a similar watch for 32 years. I have two complaints that kept me from giving five stars. First, the light on the watch isn‚Äôt bright enough to be much use‚Äî but again this is literally the view of a middle aged man. Younger or more near-sighted eyes may find the light perfectly adequate. Secondly, I actually would have appreciated a timer function and this watch doesn‚Äôt have one.

Overall, i give this four stars. Ease of use, price and ruggednesses are this watches best attributes; an inadequate light and a lack of a timer are its biggest weaknesses. So if you have $25 more to spend and don‚Äôt mind (or like) a more chunky watch, I‚Äôd recommend the Ironman Classic 30 over this watch. However, if you want to save a few bucks and your eyes are sharper than mine, the Casio is a fine choice.

I use this watch now only when I expect it to be abused (beach, travel, playing with the kids, carpentry) and it has taken everything I have thrown at it without a hiccup.  The Toyota of watches.  For a cheap, functional and nearly indestructible watch, you cannot go wrong with this.

title: Simple, minimalistic everyday watch.
text:
PROS
> Affordable
> Fits well on smaller and medium wrist sizes
> Low-profile, sleek, and very light-weight
> Long battery life
> Can take a beating
> Alarm and stopwatch
> Legible and easy to setup and use

CONS
> The backlight is near-useless, even in a pitch black room, very hard to see the display with the light on
> Resin material feels cheap
> Buttons are a bit hard to press and your wrist can hit the 12/24 hour button
> The watch wears small as advertised, be wary those with medium to larger wrists
> The strap is okay but seems to fall apart before the watch
> Only WR, other Casio watches are rated for 50m or 100m

It's a great, simple daily beater watch. It does everything it's advertised to, and it keeps time more accurate than thousand dollar timepieces. It's only $10-$15, so don't expect anything fancy. The backlight sucks and if you do need to use the watch in low light, I recommend an alternate model such as an Illuminator or one with E/L Backlight.

title: You can wear it in the shower, but it doesn't have a timer or useful stopwatch
text:
I bought this watch three months ago and have been using it daily. I was concerned about its water resistance, but it's withstood the beach, daily showers, and general everyday abuse without so much as a scratch.

It's a shame that the stopwatch function on this watch is limited to one hour‚Äîthis means that if you leave it running and forget to stop it before an hour is up, it will simply restart again at 0:00. The watch also lacks a countdown timer feature.

I also dislike the placement of the button to toggle 24 hour and 12 hour modes. It's always getting snagged on things and switching me back between time modes.

title: This is a Worthy and Charming Classic from The 70's-'80s
text: This smallish, but capable watch is a perennial favorite for those, who looking for a reliable and capable watch at an outstandingly reasonable price. Sure there are cheaper watches available on the market, but for a few dollars more than those, the buyer of this timepiece shall get a well established, reputable name, with the rock solid quality to match. The aesthetics of the watch is an added bonus for those, who like its low key, yet charming appearance. To me the only area open to criticism is the two piece stock band. Although it blends-in well with the overall design scheme, its quality doesn't quite matches up. Still, considering the price-range this watch is selling for, my criticism has to be muted. For example, (after a minor modification), I was able to replace the resin band with a more satisfactory  one piece NATO/Zulu style strap, with its sturdy metal buckle and keepers, however this cost me just about twice as much, what the watch together with its stock band cost me originally.

title: Awesome watch but Amazon lieeed to meee
text:
I bought this watch because Casio is famous for making cheap but durable watches and that's what I needed. It's lightweight and comfortable and has all the useful, standard functions in a digital watch.

I primarily use this as my "beat up" watch in that I wear it during physical activities in place of my more expensive watches. This seemed perfect for the job because of the start stop function and supposed "50 meters water resistance" which would have been able to handle the strains/needs of various workouts (e.g. running, swimming, hiking, etc.).

However upon arrival I checked the booklet and it said the level of water resistance is indicated on the back and all that is inscribed in the back of this watch is "Water Resistant" indicating it is not suitable for swimming or submersion of any kind. I have showered a few times with it on and it seems fine but I haven't tried swimming with it yet. Anyway Amazon mistakenly listed this as a watch that is water resistant up to a depth of 50 meters when in reality it is only resistant to splashes, so if you need a watch you can swim in or submerse opt for one that is truly 50 meters or above water resistant.

title: I have no complaints about thewatch itself, it does its job
text: I have no complaints about the watch itself, it does its job.  But the watchband is trash and deserves the waste basket.  The one I got was too short for my wrist, and I am not a large male.  The buckle is plastic with a plastic pin instead of metal.  This means that if the tiny short end of the plastic pin falls off, you have likely lost your watch.  The end of the pin is only about one eighth of an inch in length and one sixteenth of an inch thick.  I have seen these tips break off and that is all that is holding the watch to your wrist.  It is planned obsolescence.  The resin band on a fairly new one I purchased half broke within about a year.  That is another quick way to lose your watch.  Maybe a thicker band would help.  But I think this watch company is doing a great disservice to its customers with such a trashy watchband, and I can only think they know what they are doing and doing it on purpose.  I can only give Cassio the lowest rating.

title: The Simple Watch, for Simpler Times

Honestly, this is the watch for everyone. Do you ever go, "I wish I just had a simple clock to look at," because if you do this is the watch for you. This watch is so unapologetically simple, I can't be unhappy with it. The sheer simplicity of it brings just a little balance to a technologically controlled world.

(Note: go to time.is on any web browser or mobile device to sync your watch up to the actual time of day.)

title: Amazing watch! Update.
text:
This is the best watch I have ever owned, I absolutely love this thing. It has a simple design and it's super slim. The band feels like it will hold up to years of use. I'm a lifeguard, and it held up all summer in the water and out. Hopefully for many more to come!

Update: Writing this 2 years later, the watch is still amazing and I still love it. I wear it 24 hours a day. Sleeping, running, swimming, showering, driving, surfing the interwebs, going to school and work. The strap retainer broke about a two months ago, I put some J.B. Weld on it. It recently broke again so I am buying another one of these watches. No complaints after 2 years of 24 hr per day wear! Still the best watch I've owned as far as price, quality, and longevity are concerned. This has held up better than my friend's Luminox. In a year he had to send his in twice for service.

Wish I could give it more than 5 stars.
