title: i think the white rabbit was wearing one of these...
text:
this watch is EXACTLY what i have been looking for!
i use my watch at work all the time and have had several different ones over the last few years. while i really prefer a dial style watch, i find that the economy priced ones i have purchased tend to breal fairly quick. they dont make them like they used to. i decided to settle for a digital style watch and am so glad i got this one.
why do i like it so much?
1) its a simple design. i am pretty much fed up with this trend of watches weighing fifty pounds and having all sorts of blingy crap and dials all over the place. most of it is just for looks and when all is said and done, they just waste a lot of resources making a big hunk of junk to weigh your wrist down and get in the way. this one is fairly plain, and has the time and date clearly readable on the main screen. very straight forward without all the pseudo-tactical B.S. rambo junk.

2) it nice and SMALL. i can cover all the writing on the face of the watch with the end segment of my thumb (like making a thumb print on the screen) and it has a low,flat profile. that means you can put on a coat or shirt without it being a pain in the butt getting the watch through the sleeve.

3) its really light. you can feel your wearing it, but the sensation is subtle. wont bang around on your wrist joint and rattle you tendons like the big watches do.

4) its cheap! around 11 bucks, you cant go wrong.

5) water RESISTANT. (NOT water PROOF). this means that if you splash it while doing dishes, or get some rain on it, your not gonna have a dud at the end of the day. this is a really handy feature.

CONS:
really these are minor, but worth mention none the less.

1)the band is pretty small. it fits me fine but i have a thin wrist. i could see a person with a burly arm/wrist having a bad time with it. of course you can switch the band out, but you may not want to do that on a new watch. it fits 5.5 to 7.75 inch circumference wrist pretty comfortably, so you can check your wrist with a tape measure and see if it will work for you. the small size may be an issue for some.

2) apparently this is on the government list as a terrorist device used in making bombs or some crap. sounds like more paranoia to me, but it is a little creepie to think you could get flagged for being frugal.

thats really it on the cons. if you dont like simple watches, you wont like this. but if you want a nice practical watch that is really affordable and well made, this is a great choice. has a retro flavour too, which is fun. i hope to use this for a long time.

title: Love this watch!!
text:
I got this watch to replace my favorite white digital Casio watch that had become sort of dingy and a little scratched up from wearing 24/7 for so long. This little watch is great! It is small, which is perfect for my small wrists, and displays the time and the date, which is hard to find in a good, SMALL digital watch.
I‚Äôve worn it 24/7 since the day I got it and it is holding up really well. I‚Äôm a preschool teacher so this watch has already lived through a bunch of crafts involving paint, glue, glitter, and all kinds of other messy things and it still looks brand new. It is very easy to clean and easy to set.
I think it may be a junior size because usually I wear watches on the tightest setting and still have some wiggle room but I wear this one 2 places from the tightest setting and it‚Äôs a perfect, snug fit. It‚Äôs great for me but may be too small for a larger wrist.
ALSO, this watch is low profile so it doesn‚Äôt get caught on things and doesn‚Äôt get in the way at all.
All in all, I would highly recommend this watch. It looks nice, fits great, and is very durable AND practical.

title: When the Taliban says this sucker rocks, that's good enough for me
text: This thing is a lot like a Toyota Corolla (I have on of those, too) in that it probably is the most common watch in the world, doesn't cost much, and quietly does what its supposed to do, very reliably, for a very long time. It's got better accuracy than mechanical watches that cost thousands. It's reliably waterproof unless you are a scuba diver. I never have the battery replaced when it runs down, because in my experience, cheap watches that undergo battery replacement often are no longer waterproof (I've done a lot of swimming, free diving and sailing, also tropical rain-forest/jungle photography). When the battery goes, I just throw it away and buy another one. If you don't use the the watch's features much, the battery can last as long as seven years. Mine tend to die at four years because I use the light a lot and also the stopwatch, which runs for many hours because I usually forget to shut it off. Sex appeal? Zero. This watch is guaranteed to never get you laid. Stylishness? Zero. Maybe even minus zero since this watch screams "Cheap Cheap! Cheap!!" even from a distance. And it's good for the environment because it is made out of recycled sandwich bags. This is the watch you want when all you care about is maximum reliability and durability, and you don't need to impress anybody. Mullah Omar (peace be upon him) says: "Check it out, Bubba!"

title: Ideal Functional Watch
text:
This is the ideal functional watch, especially for casual use.
It tells the time accurately, forever; and it has many handy features like a stop watch, timer and alarm.
The cost is very low, so when the battery runs out--maybe 10 years? More? throw it away. Your math is right, that is about a $1 a year for this reliable technology.

I do believe that everyone in a business setting should have a nice watch. Save for that, and spend what it takes to maintain it.

However, outside of the boardroom, the Casio is simply ideal as to form and function. After 40 years of wearing this model or ones very much like it, they have never broken and they take a beating.

Finally, contributing to the perfect nature of the watch, it is not gigantic as so many watches sold today. The best measure of a man's watch should be its ability to function, and also be inconspicuous. Of course, if you want to be showy, there are plenty of clown watches for sale.

title: Good looking watch but very small characters
text:
I bought one of these for my 11-yr old nephew as his first Casio watch. I chose the olive green version which looks really cool. Because I own a Casio EA-1000W, decided not to order another F91W for myself, and I am glad I didn't.

Nothing wrong with the watch itself though: it's very easy to set up and all the information is correctly placed on the screen. The only issue I found is that the characters are very small for me. I wear readers and even though, I struggled to read it properly until I found the appropriate distance to look at it from. I also tried it on, and found it very small for my wrist. The watch itself is so small and light, that it almost feels like a toy watch.

But what matters is that my nephew loved it and it was a great fit for his wrist. He is tall for his age but I trust he will keep it for many years until he outgrows it.

I would recommend this watch to anyone who does not have bad eye sight, and big arms or wrist. I you have eye sight issues like myself, I would look at other options. It's not the watch , it's me :D

title: Classic Watch With Timeless Utility
text:
There is a reason that the Casio F91W-1 has been on the market for nearly three decades: it works. The timekeeping is accurate, it can easily be synced with the seconds zero feature, and it is lightweight & comfortable; I often forget that I'm wearing it. What surprises me most about this little watch is how tough it is. We're not talking about a G-Shock here, but I've had this watch slammed against walls, appliances, and heavy equipment without leaving a scratch.

If you need an inexpensive watch that can take a beating and reliably tell you the time, look no further!

title: In production 25 years, though the strap is a weak point
text:
I have a few of these one bought back in 1991 when the F-91W had just come out. The design is pure Casio and distinctive, though the features at the time were fairly good (alarm, 1/100th sec chronograph, 12/24 hour and date format - no year though) it's not the main reason for looking at one. More of a blast to the past and a nod to the design.

Water resistant to 30 metres (and they are WR unlike some), green LED back light it's a basic watch and with a good battery life... I get around 5/6 years on the watches I have used and worn. It's a bog standard but appealing Casio, so popular in fact far eastern makers have copied the design minus the obvious Casio logo.

Now the weakest part by far isn't the case which is pretty tough as is the transparent cover over the display; The resin strap is prone to failure if you tend to wear a watch all the time (by that I mean all day long even at night) you will likely encounter the strap failure issue; it's also a bit smaller than most watches making it unsuitable for those with larger wrists (quite a good fit for kids and most adults but if you have larger wrists beware - it's 22.3cm or just over 8.6 inches long from tip to tip). You can replace it or not worry about if it you only occasionally wear the watch. There are higher end models around with larger displays and more snazzy features, this just has an appeal that continues to grow even to this day.

title: Superb watch - a few small differences from the classic F-91W
text:
I own a bunch of G-Shocks, and the DW-290, but at the end of the day, the F-91W wins out. Nothing comes close in terms of lightness, comfort, and reliability, and this version is no different.
I don't know if this has been mentioned by many reviewers, but I just wanted to point out a few small differences between this olive green model and the original black one:
1) For whatever reason, the strap on this one is just a hair shorter (see photo).
2) The LCD screen of the green model is *slightly* worse than that of the original - text is less sharp/clear.
3) As the band on the green model is slightly shorter, the spacing between the holes is slightly different - meaning the two watches will not fit exactly the same.

That said, none of these are dealbreakers in any way; the green is faintly metallic (almost has a glitter sheen to it), and looks great, and the functionality and performance are identical to the original. Well worth the money!

title: Certified 100% accurate description of man's greatest invention to follow
text:
Certified 100% accurate description of man's greatest invention to follow:
The watch is controlled by three side-mounted pushbuttons. The upper left button turns on the backlight, cancels the alarm, and is used for selecting settings. Holding the backlight button for 5 seconds activates a high intensity stream of energy that can be used to ignite things; intended for cigars. The lower left button cycles the modes of the watch: time display, alarm, stopwatch, and time adjustment. The button on the right is the function button: when used it starts and stops the stopwatch, changes the settings currently being adjusted, or switches between the 12- and 24-hour modes, depending on what mode the watch is currently in.

The time or date is adjusted by pressing the lower left button three times to bring the watch to time adjustment mode. The top left button is used to cycle through seconds, hours, minutes, month, date, day, and normal mode. The right button is used to adjust the flashing value displayed. When the adjustments are finished, the bottom left button can be pressed once to return the watch to normal mode.

The watch display shows the day of the week, day of the month, hour, minute, seconds, and the signs PM or 24H ([[24-hour clock]]), the alarm signal status, and the hourly signal status (double beep on the hour). The watch emits a gamma pulse that optimizes the strength of the wearer's muscle tissue.

title: A solid water-resistant watch, but uncomfortable wrist and unreliable date
text: This watch is very water resistant and practical. I've taken it in the shower, a spring, and a pool and had no problems. Two things I don't like is how it feels and how easily the date switches on its own. The wrist part is made of of a material that kind of sticks to you like your skin does to certain fabrics on a hot summer day. It's really irritating to me, but I'm sensitive to that. My solution has been to wear it as loose as possible. A more annoying problem is that that the day of the week and date keep changing themselves. I think the button gets pressed as I am moving about. This is bad if you think it's one day and its actually not. I usually catch it and correct it, but that facilitates the need for a phone which contradicts the whole reason why I bought the watch, to not use my phone. I think you get what you pay for and it's fine if you need a watch for the most basic purpose of time. I have not found a need for the other functions, but they seem easy enough to work after you read the instruction manual. I have had the watch for about a month and it's already a bit scratched up. I think that's okay, but it goes to show that it is not that resilient.

title: Like a long lost friend
text: I had a Casio F91W wrist watch for many, maybe over ten, years. Last fall, I could not get the watch reset and I had lost the instructions. I tossed the watch in a drawer and occasionally tried to reset it. I looked in a few stores but could not find an equivalent watch. Then I tried Amazon and much to my surprise found an identical watch at a very good price and instantly ordered a new Casio F91W. While waiting for the watch to be delivered, somehow I magically got the old watch reset but it still needed a new wrist band. The new watch was delivered in short time and I was happy to have a new replacement for the old watch. The best thing was that it was identical to the old watch which had served me so well.

But the backlight is not the full screen on some other name brand watches. It is a small, weak light on the far left of the face that only really illuminates the hour and not the minute. As someone who checks what time it is while laying in bed, this was a let down.

For 10 bucks, it would make a good watch for a kid or wife to have a burner watch, but that is it. In my opinion, go with the 30 dollar casios that arent knockdown models.

title: This is a 4 year review
text: I bought this watch 4 years ago as a daily beater watch. I've worn it in sub-zero F conditions, rain, snow, scorching heat, went swimming with it, and it is still going strong. I haven't had the need to change the battery yet.

title: Great, Cheap Watch
text:
I've only had this watch for maybe a month or two, but most of the the existing positive reviews seem to be spot on. I have higher-end automatic watches for work and dress but for the weekend, this is perfect. I don't have to worry about hitting it on things or scratching it because although it seems to be well constructed and I fully expect it will last a long time, at this price point, it's almost disposable.

Most anything that can be said about this watch at this point has been said since it's been around for a while, but a few brief thoughts.

It has alarm functionality that works and even though I usually use my cell phone as my alarm, it's nice to have the option if for whatever reason I am without my phone (e.g. camping). Also has a stopwatch. It is water resistant, although I'm not sure I'd go swimming with it. The water resistance ratings on watches tend to be overly optimistic and based on lab conditions - so for example, I'd consider something that indicates 50M water resistance (like this watch) to be suitable for a shower and maybe some light swimming - but a dive watch, this is not.

Other features are day and date which are nice as well (I find it somewhat funny you'd probably pay $10K+ for an automatic watch with that functionality).

The illumination is not cast evenly across the face, but it does illuminate enough to see the numbers clearly, which is really all you need.

Only negative is probably on the fashion front, but that's not enough to deduct a star since it's such a subjective factor. I think it does have a kind of retro-cool look to it, but my wife detests the watch. Her main issue, and one that I can understand, is that the face is so small, it looks almost comical on my wrist, and I don't have huge wrists. But again, not worth deducting a star.

title: For two gallons of gas and a bigmac it is pretty good
text:
This watch has its pros and cons which I will list below.

+Nice size, Not some bulky monstrosity like so many watches today, doesn't crowd your wrist with a baseball sized gaudy trinket.
+Easy fast setup
+long battery life (allegedly, have not had for as many years as the claimed battery life)
+easy to switch between 12/24 hour setup (dedicated button actually)
+feels like a quality piece, the band doesn't feel cheap like it is going to snap in half (the buckle is a different story, I think it is plastic, it as not failed me but I question its long term durability)
+uncluttered display, not too much information being shown at once, just day, date, and time.
+Good waterproofing, easily survives taking daily showers, and the plastic band does not absorb moisture and shot never rot or mold.
lots of adjustment points, will fit a child's wrist as easily as a full grown mans.

~neutral considerations~

being made of rubber or plastic, the band will make you sweat against it, especially if it is humid like it has been around me lately.

Negatives
-NOT made in the US, Made in Thailand according to the back of the watch.
- the lighting feature is cheesy, it only lights up one half of the watch (unless mine is broken) and it is almost unnoticeable unless you are in a very dark room, better hope you only need to know the hour and MAYBE the minutes, because the seconds are basically completely dark.

for 11 dollars, why not, if you want or need a good budget watch that doesn't look awful, this very well may be the watch for you.

It gives you the time (in your choice of 12-or 24-hour display modes), day and date, has an alarm function (the alarm on this is louder than the ones on some of my G Shocks, which cost a lot more!!) and a stopwatch.  It‚Äôs a small watch, light and comfortable to wear, and its positive LCD display is easy to read.  So what‚Äôs not to like?  The backlight.  It‚Äôs never been a strong point for the F-91W. It barely lights one side of the screen, but for me, that‚Äôs not extremely important, because I‚Äôm rarely in situations where I need to tell time in the dark, and if I think I will be, I have other watches with better backlights.  Overall, for its super-low price, quality construction and value for money, I‚Äôm giving the F-91W five stars.

title: Excellent value for this watch
text:
By no means is this some high tech 200 dollar watch, but it is a light weight, high value, and useful watch. There isn't much else you could want from a watch.

The four features of the watch are all you need. You've got your regular time setting, dual time, a stop watch, and best of all, an alarm clock. Along with this, the watch is water proof. What a bargain!

The instructions for the watch are simple, and setting it up is a breeze so long as you can read. Figuring out the alarm clock was a bit tricky, but after doing it a few times, it come naturally. Once you have all the settings set you should be able to toggle back and forth from settings with ease.

The dual time feature is useful when traveling or keeping up with loved ones in other parts of the world. You can also choose between 24 hour or 12 hour time settings with one press of a button.

For ten dollars you shouldn't expect the best made watch. I've had it for a month now and can already tell that it can't take a beating, so I recommend taking caution with it. In the end though, this watch is a great deal if all you need is a simple watch with an alarm clock.

title: When on sale, it's less expensive to buy a new one than to replace the strap
text:
The strap on my old casio watch gave up after several years of daily abuse. You'll pay less here than at Target or WalMart, and if it's on any kind of sale or discount, it's cheaper to buy a new one here than to get a new band.

I love this thing: it's a simple, no BS timepiece that includes a stopwatch and alarm with hourly chime. I'm not a really heavy sleeper and the alarm is more than enough to wake me up in the morning. It doesn't say "look at me, i have a fancy expensive watch," and, quite frankly, it tells time just as effectively for day-to-day use as something costing exponentially more. I've left these things submerged in water overnight, and my last one even went through the laundry twice. It's a tank, a rock, a perfect example of function over form... and the form isn't even truly bad, either.

title: Really my favorite casual watch
text:
I have several dress watches, but for everyday wear, I wear this watch. Why? Because it has an alarm feature, a stop watch, date, time, day of the week and so on. I bang these up pretty good, so I don't want to spend a ton of money.

That said, this watch is certainly not perfect. The case used to be made out of a solid block of stainless steel. Not anymore! The case is now made out of resin...plastic, in other words. I can get maybe a year out of the watch, then the area where the band attaches to the watch, fractures and the watch is now useless. Saves replacing the battery, I guess. I wish they would make a better mount for the band. Then, the watch would be fantastic!

But, for the price, it's a good deal. Just plan on buying one every year.

title: The Gold Standard Practical Watch
text:
What could I say about an F91W that hasn't been said? It's a lightweight waterproof watch with a chrono/stopwatch, alarm, backlight, and costs $10 with a battery that probably lasts 5 years plus. It is the ultimate utility watch, that asks nothing of you and will take essentially any amount of abuse. Break it? Oh well, $10 for another one that's exactly like the one you have.

In the year or so I've had this one I've cleaned blood out of the buttons with peroxide, sanitized it daily with bleach wipes, swam in oceans with it, even used it as an alarm clock when the power was out. It's a force to be reckoned with, and if I sold one of my mechanical watches I could buy one of these for every single person who works in my department and still have a thousand dollars left over.

In short, highly recommended.

title: Disposable by choice
text: There‚Äôs something that feels strangely pro-consumer about this watch. Growing up, I‚Äôve always assumed it impossible to find a quality product at 1/10th the price of the competition; however I‚Äôve happily replaced my old expensive watch with this cheap Casio, and haven‚Äôt looked back. The display is readable in any condition and the watch / included band are very comfortable and light on the wrist. I first tried out the more expensive Casio ‚Äúworld traveler‚Äù watch, and it wasn‚Äôt comfortable whatsoever. This tiny Casio F91w feels like a much smarter option. It‚Äôs disposable by choice, the watch won‚Äôt force you to throw it out for a replacement but if you can if you want. So far, I haven‚Äôt noticed much time loss, but with how easy it is to set the watch, if it started falling out of sync updating it would be no problem. I really enjoy this product, and I hope Casio doesn‚Äôt discontinue it anytime soon as I intend on making this my main watch for years to come.

title: Awesome watch Great on a NATO or Zulu strap
text:
First off I had to put it on a Zulu strap because the stock resin band is was way to short. It was not even long enough to completely go around my 8 3/4 inch wrist, I bought this already knowing this point So fyi the review will reflect it on a NATO or Zulu strap not on the stock resin band
Pros.
1.Very light weight on a NATO or Zulu strap. You barley know know its there through out the day. It don't feel like a boat anchor on your wrist.
2.The alarm and hourly chime is loud it is about 2 times loud as my G-Shock GWM5610
3.Price,if you are on a budget and need a reliable time piece I recommend this and a after market NATO strap .
4. It gives me nostalgic feelings back to the late 80's when my dad wore a f91 .
5.Seven year average battery life is great.
6.The case back is stainless steel with 4 screws and a gasket ,not a snap back case you would expect at this price point
7.Quartz accuracy. I don't need to say more.
8.The digits are easy to read.
Cons
1.The light only lights up from the left side and is only good in complete darkness.
2..Taking That strap off and putting on a NATO strap was a pain, I ended up using regulars spring bars and spring bar tool ,Recommend searching "Casio F91W NATO strap" on the internet if you plan on putting one on, or are thinking about it.
3.The watch crystal is acrylic resin ,and will Scratch.
4.The size is small to todays standards of bigger watches if that bothers you this is not the watch for you and look at the bigger digital watches Casio offers.
5.Some might say the it feels cheap with the case made of resin.
6.If you have a big wrist you have to go with a after market strap.

In conclusion this is my new go to field / beater watch and cant beat value for what you get .

title: Cool digital watch!
text:
I own a couple quartz watches, an automatic watch, and wanted to try out a digital watch. For digital watches, Casio is the go-to! I got this style because I liked the classic sleek design, and I wanted one with a bit of matte gold to somewhat match with my matte gold wedding band.

I love this watch. I use it as my daily. I don't have to worry about trashing it, losing it, or getting it stolen for the reason that it's so affordable for the average person that I can always replace it with a new one. I've worn it on a vacation trip and wore it in the pool/ocean for hours without any damage.

I also like how understated it is, which is the style I go for. It makes a statement that you don't care about showing off your money on your wrist, at the same time having a nostalgic 80s feel.

title: Easy controls, thin and comfortable, geeky/cool
text:
I admit I ordered this because it's been in the news. (If you don't understand, google "Casio terrorism"). Now that I have it, I am surprisingly pleased with it as a watch, rather than as an ironic accessory.

I like watches, but hate paying a lot for them. The problem is that inexpensive ones usually aren't very comfortable to wear, don't look that good, don't last, and have difficult controls. Every one of these things is not true for this Casio. Right out of the box, it was appealing. The resin strap isn't cheap looking, the watch itself is thin and light. Very readable face. I didn't even have to read the instructions to understand how to use all the controls. It's understated but retro enough to be cool in a geeky way.

I can't swear to it's durability since I've had it only for a day. I'll update this after I've used it for a while.

title: No longer 5 star
text:
I have another Casio, G-Shock G7700, I bought this F-91W for daily use when I don't need G-shock for sport. F-91W's not applicable for sport, but it's just enough.

The G7700 is a little too big for daily use, and I have to take it off when I sleep for its shape make me uncomfortable. The biggest problem is the strap keep accumulating nasty white thing in its gap and web pattern, I need to clean it really often. Design of it is awful, they didn't consider how it really feel. Therefore, I chose this one.

For F-91W:

Pros:
1. Light weight, 20g vs 52g of G-shock, I can't feel it on my wrist.
2. The strap is easy to clean and smooth.
3. Cost less, it covered 99% percent of daily time use. I don't think many people need a world time and an 1/1000 stopwatch.

Cons:
1. Only three operation button, and one blank slot.
2. If I can be 2-3mm bigger, it would be perfect.

Overall, it's a good watch for the price and normal casual occasions.
-----------Update 2014/1/25--------------
I changed the rating from 5 stars to 1 star.

The old one went swimming with me, hot shower with me without any problem.

I just got a new one 2 days ago, broke in less than 48 hours, during my first swimming with it.

Unacceptable.

title: Great affordable versatile watch.
text:
Cult classic and justly so. If you've never tried one, you will likely be pleasantly surprised. Of course it looks exactly like what it is, a cheap watch; but a good one. Try not to bend the strap back over the buckle like you would with a leather strap and it will last a lot longer. I have and enjoy other more expensive watches from Citizen, Seiko, Rotary; this Casio gets a lot of wear time. When the strap eventually does break, a NATO type seems to be the popular choice for a replacement. Very long-wearing. Read some reviews for this watch. I learned a thing or two.

Cons: Sometimes the buttons can be inadvertently pushed. Visibility in some lighting conditions may be lacking. If you really snag the strap it can break or tear. If the little keeper breaks the strap may soon break too, right at the buckle. The light is a bit weak.

Pros: Light as a feather. Adjustable to a wide range of wrist sizes, so a fun choice for a child's watch. Many colours to pick from. Digital display, if you've never had one, is instant and positive. For some people, reading an analog face can be confusing, especially when one is used to am / pm, and confronted with 24 hour times; when you are traveling and are tired, for example. So the ability to swap the display between am / pm or 24 hours is a plus. The alarm is useful. Materials are more unaffected by sweat, saltwater, and grime than a leather strap. So, useful as a work watch, or for many outdoors activities. Very inexpensive, almost disposable. Widely available, so easily replaced. Long battery life. Operation of buttons and features is easy.

Very highly recommended!

title: I love wearing a watch so I bought a really nice ...
text:
Over a year ago I went on a minimalist kick, ditched everything that I didn't use and spent money on higher quality objects that I did use... I love wearing a watch so I bought a really nice analogue (tick-tock) watch. About 4 months after my purchase the second hand on my analogue watch fell off under the glass and jammed itself between the hour and the minute hand...pissed about it I jumped on amazon picked out this watch that I had as a kid, was at least three times cheaper than my analogue watch, smaller, lighter... and way more useful.

I am extremely happy with this watch (again), it's easy to read in any light, it's comfortable, light weight, it beeps on every hour so I kinda have an idea of how fast time is moving when I'm working, it has an alarm that can remind me when to do whatever, and a stop-watch function that comes in handy from time to time for taking pulse or jogging. One of my favorite features though is that it clearly states the day and date, I always use my watch for the date when taking notes or what have you.

If anything ever happens to this watch I will be buying this same one again.

text:
This watch does exactly what a watch is supposed to do. I love the looks I get and conversations with people with expensive watches on their wrist.

Actual stranger encounter-
Stranger: *looks at my watch* Wow, what is that?!
Me: A watch.
Stranger: How come you don't have a smartwatch?
Me: I spent $15 dollars on mine, how much was yours?
Stranger: *looks at her Apple watch* I'm not sure how much it is. I make payments on it.
Me: Wait... you financed a watch?!

Every time I look down at my wrist, it reminds me that money is much better spent on something else. Can't believe people spend $400+ on a sad excuse for a fashion statement that will be obsolete in a year.

Also, the retro look is pretty cool.

title: Best Watch I've Ever Had
text:
I bought this product when I got a job that required me to pretty heavily keep track of the time. The water resistance and the stopwatch really sold me on the product, so I went ahead and placed my order.

After using this product for a week I loved it. This is, by far, the best watch I have ever had. It is easy to use, quick to read from, and always accurate. I will, however, issue a warning on the product.....

After I used my casio for a year one of the buttons on the side jammed and I was no longer able to switch screens from the clock to the alarm to the stopwatch. HOWEVER, it needs to said that I wear my watch everyday, all day long AND I use that button multiple times a day to time various tasks I am assigned to do. If you do not need to time things or use the alarm very often, I highly doubt you will have this problem.

With that being said, this product was so wonderful and easy to use that, despite that, I still ordered a brand new one when my original casio jammed. And that is the ONLY problem I have ever had with the watch. I have absolutely no other complaints.

In short: I highly recommend buying this product, even if you, like myself, use it so much that it breaks within the year. For the amount you pay for it and with all of its functions and features, it is still highly worth it and is a very good product.

title: Functional and inexpensive, nice color choice
text: The Casio F-91W is a favorite among terrorists and cheapskates. This version has a case color that is metallic grey. It looks pretty nice. It is similar to the color used on a lot of electronics. This watch is a perfect match to my Logitech mouse, my computer speakers, and my electric razor!

title: Casio F91
text: This watch cost less than eating a steak from the restaurant or eating two fast food meal or two cup of delicious coffee from well known coffee shop. Any body can skip a couple of good meals and save the money to buy this watch that will last them for several years. Benefit for wearing this watch is: Will not make you look rich, muggers will probably look at you and judge you by looking at the cheap looking watch and think you are a poor guy and not worth trying to rob you. Don't wear this watch for going into an expensive watch boutique that is very well known for sponsoring major golf events or yacht races, the sales person won't help you at all after looking at your wrist watch. Your friends or family probably won't ask to borrow money from you when you wear this watch. This watch keeps good time, I like it.

title: Good, Basic, and Cheap Watch
text:
I purchased this for a little more than 8 bucks after seeing it mentioned in a "dealzmodo" post on gizmodo. For what it is, it's a nice little watch.

It's very small and light. You will forget you're even wearing it as soon as you put it on your wrist. It has a very thin profile so it won't catch on your pocket or other things when reaching into tight spaces. The band is a little on the shorter size. I have about a 7" wrist circumference and this is about the largest the watch will accommodate comfortably. I usually wear it on the 3rd or 4th hole from the end. It's pretty tight for me when wearing it on the 4th. It feels better on the 3rd but then the little band that slides over the the excess strap after it's buckled doesn't have much to hold on to and slides off very easily. If you wear it on the 1st or second hole, you won't even be able to utilize the little band the the end of the watch strap will always stick out from your wrist. The band quality is also not the greatest. I'm sure it would break within a couple years if you wear it regularly. However, you can't really expect more for the price.

The mineral display is very clear and easy to read. Since the bezel is flush with the screen, it would probably be pretty easy to scratch if you rubbed it up against a wall or something. There is a small green LED light on the left side of the display that can be activated to view the time in the dark. It could be better, but it lights up the screen just enough to be able to view all the characters in the dark.

It's rather light on features but has all the main ones you would need in a basic digital watch. Time (12 and 24 hour), date, stopwatch, and alarm (with hourly chime option). It keeps great time too.

Overall, this is a great watch for the money. I bought it to wear in situations where I don't want to risk harm to my G-Shock MTG-900. You don't have to be careful with this one. It can be abused and if it breaks or is lost, you're only out about $10 and it can easily be replaced. 5 stars easily.

text: So my Timex indiglo broke after a few years of trusty service, and I decided I didn‚Äôt want to spend oodles of money for a replacement, and I wanted to go digital. While my first choice for the f91w was classic all-black, the silver-black has really grown on me. Of course it tells the time. But it also has a stopwatch, an alarm, and a day-date feature like any good chronograph. The resin band can get sweaty, but this watch is really light and unobtrusive. The light is trash, but it does provide barely enough luminescence to tell the time in a pitch-black environment. title: The Glock of digital watches
text:
First: What Amazon calls "white" is actually the silver model. Do not order a "white" one expecting a white case.

To the review:

This watch is good. My usual hesitation with digital watches is that they are extremely overcomplicated, with alarms I do not know how to shut off (or set), etc. G shocks, Suuntos, etc, are all good watches if you need all their features. However, I do not. I expect most people do not. Most people need the time and date, and the Casio does this, and it does this well.

I also like 24 hour time, and this is only possible on digital watches, unless you track down a Soviet submariner watch, which I don't want to do.

This is the Glock of digital watches. Like a Glock shoots every time, and nothing else, the F-91W tells the time, date, and not much else. It has an alarm and a stopwatch if you are into that. They are unobtrusive features if you do not go in for them. The buttons do not get accidentally pressed, the housing is very low profile.

I have only had this for a couple of days, so we will see on durability, but anecdotally these can take a lot of abuse.

This would also be a good first watch for kids or for a elderly person who just wants a thing that can tell time.

The LED light is a touch dim. According to how good your vision is, you might not be able to see the minutes and seconds, but you will probably be able to see the hour.

title: The BEST WATCH under $15.  Terrorist or not.
text:
Well. I contemplated for some time if I should write a review for this ultra affordable watch or not ... after some thoughts, this Casio deserves every bit of my highest recommendations so I decided to go for it

If you are reading this ... either you stumbled on the F91W-1 by looking at some of the cheapest Amazon stocked watches
Or you read from Wikipedia, or some watch forums, or other sources that this Casio is the favorite among the terrorist group.

Well regardless what your motivation is ... this watch is worth every penny.

Some background information. I been collecting mechanical watches for about 16+ years. And right now I own over 50 watches... From this humble $11 Casio to a few Rolex, Zenith, Omega, JLC that cost 500 times its price. I also service some of my own mechanical pieces. Although I do not have much experience with quartz watches. I do know quite a bit about material, design and many aspects of a proper horological machine.

And the down right truth is, there is nothing this Casio can't do. As far as a practical machine, it can beat up your datejust/ submariner any day of the week. (Although this might not be that big of a deal in todays cell phone oriented world)

Pros:
It is designed to be simple and intuitive, the trait of most Casios. Button placement and functions are down right instinctive once you use it for a day or two.

It is deadly accurate (duh), its quartz.

The battery life is an amazing 7 years (given you use certain functions only once or twice a day.) Although some "upgraded" version has 10 year or solar battery. The battery life is more then reasonable for any practical purpose.

This is the most comfortable watch I own, due to one reason - the weight. It feels like you are wearing a feather or nothing at all. 20 grams to be exact... or 0.7oz. Crazy how light this thing is.

The retro styling is another plus .. it may not have been cool in the 80~90s. The nerdy black resin square case is now hip again...

The construction of this watch is very well thought out to simplify the manufacturing process. Which, btw, is done in Thailand. Case is a single piece resin with slightly protruding plastic crystal. All the electronics are on a one piece of ic board. The case back is made from stamped stainless steel, secured by 4 screws, and the interior is where the alarm speaker goes. A rather large rubber gasket surrounds the movement. Light weight rubber strap with some mysterious reflective inclusion.

Cons
Water resistance: The case construction does not allow any serious form of water resistance... as a matter of fact, in the Casio manual they do not recommend anything more then hand washing. The real problem is the pushers, they lack any gasket so water will pour in when use underwater. The tolerance of the case and SS back is decent. But the gasket sits too low so a 100% secure seal will not be possible. Crystal seems to be glued into place, so no problem with water there. I think degrees of water resistance is how Casio separates their cheapest products from the slightly more expensive one.

You can hear something rattle when you shake this watch ... it is nothing major however

If you are used to today's super large watch... namely, Graham, Panerai, 44mm, 50mm or the likes. This watch will look puny to you at 35mm. But if you like most watches in the 70s or 80s ... this is just the right size.

The bottom line is ... this is a hell of a watch for the money. As utilitarian as it could be yet possess some of the funk from the past decades. It also carries a good amount of interesting back stories if you tell people about its popularity among the terrorists. A great watch! And the best $9.99 I spend on a watch.

title: The F91W fits my wrist really well (4th from the last hole) with a comfortable fit. Perhaps it is just luck
text:
The Casio F91W-1 is a minimal, well designed, and very accurate watch.

I have fairly small wrists for a male and I've always found watches hard to wear ‚Äî I usually have to use the last hole on the strap with a lot of excess strap hanging out of the holder. The F91W fits my wrist really well (4th from the last hole) with a comfortable fit.

Perhaps it is just luck, but I've found my particular F91W to be very accurate comparing it to time.gov and a clock that auto synchronizes with NIST. I've been comparing it to 2 Casio A158Ws I purchased around the same time and both of those lose a couple of seconds per week while the F91W continues to remain accurate.

This watch has been known to be popular among terrorists who have used it to make ticking time bombs and has even been used as significant evidence used to keep prisoners in Guantanamo Bay.
In a very ironic way, sharing a watch which has so much controversy behind it gives it a cult value that you just can't find in other watches.
Otherwise, the watch is very practical to use. Cheap enough so that you don't have to worry about scratching its surface but still very reliable in its mechanics and very cool in its simplistic style. It is a smaller piece, very suitable for guys like me with small wrists and small arms.
This watch has been in production for 25 years now since 1991 which is telling of its popularity and value.

title: A reliable and nostalgic classic
text:
This was the first watch my parents bought me when I was a child so this purchase definitely has a lot of sentimental value for me.
Despite the price, this watch is built to last, and I am only talking about the face of the watch. As others have mentioned, the band does not seem like it will stand the test of time although it has not broken for me as of yet. Should it happen in the future I'll likely replace it with a 18mm Nato strap. The watch has pretty basic functions including current time with seconds (military time is possible), current day of the week, current date, stop watch, alarm, and not so strong night light that mostly illuminates the left interface of the watch (the only part I wish could improve).
As for the wrist band size, I am an adult man and have no issue with it however I can see how it may run small for those with very wide wrists.
For the price you really cannot go wrong with such a reliable and basic watch. I own much pricier watches and I would not be surprised if this watch outlives them. I currently use it when traveling, going to gym and even for corporate setting (I love it that much).

title: Timeless timepiece
text: The Casio F91W-1 is the original. Like the Ray-Ban Wayfarer, the Clarks Desert Boot, or Levi's 501s, this watch started a trend and has been imitated ever since. I've owned all sorts of digital watches over the years, from the inexpensive to the unreasonably pricey (Suunto Core comes to mind, batteries only lasted six months and started resetting its own time after nine) but in the end I come back to this watch. You can't find more value for your money. Classic styling, precise quartz movement, 12 and 24 hour time, day, date, alarm, chronograph, light, and water resistance all for $10. You'd be stupid to buy anything else. This watch is a conversation piece. It's retro without being ironic; it's as elegant as it is rugged. Bravo, Casio. Bravo.

title: The ur-digital watch. It's perfectly imperfect, is both more and less than you think.
text:
The F91W (named with letters and numbers in true Casio fashion) is a modern classic. It is the ur-digital watch. Is it perfect? No, but also yes. It is very affordable compared to almost all other watches, yet made with a respect for quality that far exceeds the no-name watches on drugstore racks. Like all classics, it is both more and less than its reputation.

How is it less? Well, it would be nice to have a dedicated light button so that you didn't have to activate the light every time you wanted to change the alarm time or reset the stopwatch--yes, the light goes on whenever you press that top-left button in any mode. I can't complain about the light itself, which is a yellow-green and charmingly weak LED, because the F105W model exists for those who want a bright, uniform backlight, and it costs about the same amount as this watch with just a slightly different appearance. It would be nice if the strap were attached with spring bars instead of push-through pins. But these may be necessary measures to keep the cost low, and they speak to the watch's approach of functional economy and simplicity above all else.

How is the F91W more than its reputation? There's a grace in a product that does one or a few things as well as you need it to and doesn't strive to impress with unnecessary bells and whistles. That is the nature of the F91W. It tries only to be what you need it to be and succeeds beautifully. Its design, form, and function are in harmony, and that is a rare and lovely quality for a consumer product. Am I a hipster for wearing this watch? Perhaps, but its reputation as the everyman's timepiece is so strong that it can't be pigeonholed into an emblem for a single group of people.

The F91W is not a large watch. I have a moderately sized 6.75" wrist, and I would argue that it is well-proportioned for my wrist, though much smaller than most watches that I wear. If you are willing to broaden your perception of how big a watch should be to include a size that would have been at home on your grandfather's wrist, you will like this watch. Sometimes I want a larger watch, but often I really appreciate that this one is so slim and light that it doesn't get in my way, doesn't hang up on my cuffs, and doesn't press into the back of my hand when I bend my wrist back. I would probably buy this again if it were lost or broken, and at the price I paid of $10.20 + tax in January 2015, it would be affordable to do so.

title: ~7.25" = max wrist size
text:
I've had it on for less than an hour, so I'll edit my review after it's gotten some real usage, but for those concerned about the band size:
The user guide says not to wear it too tight; you should be able to slide one finger underneath the band while it's on your wrist.

It fits my ~6 inch wrist just fine.

For the benefit of others looking into this watch, I loosened it and fastened the buckle in the last hole and slid it up my forearm until it fit, but while I was still able to fit a finger underneath the band and my arm.

You should probably never buy a watch that only fits using the last hole. With this watch, the loop that holds the end of the band in place can't even cover the band end when loosened to this degree.

The largest wrist this could *accommodate* would be 7.5" in diameter.

The largest wrist this could fit comfortably on would be below 7.25"

title: Classy, in a $10 sorta way
text:
The Casio Fox 91 Whiskey (F91W) is a classic that makes a statement: "You don't have a whole lot of money, but you do have a whole lot of class."
The F91W is extremely easy to operate, even for those who can't program the time on a VCR.
It's versatile. One time zone. An alarm. Stop watch with laps. It does it all!
Water resistance? You bet your bottom dollar! Swim with it. Shower with it. Pretty soon the F91W will be your new best friend!
When someone sees this on your wrist they'll know that you love the classic futuristic look of the past and you're not afraid to show it!
The F91W will always keep you on time. In one time zone.

title: Perfect for daily use
text:
This watch impresses me. Every now and then I will come across a design that has no conceivable room for improvement. This is typically reserved for things like nail clippers or disposable lighters.

Why this watch is so great:
7(!) year battery
stopwatch (1 hour max)
12/24 hour time
tough: strap is comfortable and the pins are strong, the crystal is easily scratched, but the scratches don't reduce the readability.
day of the week / day of the month
keeps time very well
backlight

Somehow this watch sells for <$15, which not only makes it unattractive to anyone who would want to steal it, but makes its potential loss only the most minor of tragedies, which in its own way is a great feature. I have seen watches with identical interfaces but made by companies that aren't Casio. The imitators just do not have the battery life or the understated elegance of this beauty. I don't swim very frequently and I never go diving, but it holds up great in the shower.

title: Every single F91 I received from Amazon was flawed
text: The F91W is a great watch, but I'd recommend finding a different source than Amazon for them if you want the best F91 you can get. I went through 3 watches from amazon, every single one had varying degrees of noticeable bubbling in the crystal. My f91 purchased in a local watch store and one I purchased directly from Casio did not have these issues at all. The watches still function, they're authentic and keep good time. If you don't care about finish flaws and just need a functional watch, definitely snag one here for the cheap price.

I currently have a piece of duct tape fixed on there to keep the watch strap secured, but I really wish that piece were more sturdy.

title: Casio F91W-1 Classic
text:
The reason why I gave this product 5 stars is because:
-Cheap price;
-Digital watch;
-The timer.

One personal negative thing about this watch for me is that it is water resistant instead of water proof. I started swimming a couple of months before I had bought this watch, and I want to have a timer for my swimming exercises. I only looked for a cheap watch with a timer, and I forgot to look for the purpose of swimming (and thus water proof instead of water resistant), but it is my own fault. Because of the previous typed reason; I have to buy a new watch which is water proof instead of water resistant. I will still wear this watch outside the swimming pool.

text:
fine to abuse. takes water like a champ, got a scratch on it and didn't care at all.

I ended up liking the "poor quality" light. if it's pitch black out and you want to check the time, regular watch lights can be pretty glaring. this one is dim enough to not punch you in the eye, and still -just- bright enough to illuminate the screen.

as far as practicality goes im happy with this. if i can get a few years out of it i'd happily buy another. Will update if there is some sort of major failure.

title: Best Watch Ever!!
text: To start this watch is AMAZING. I'm simple when it comes to accessories. The only reason I bought a watch was because I needed one for my job which is Parasailing and Boat Rentals. I needed to keep track of time. I've been reading a few reviews and a lot talk about that's it not great with water besides washing hands. I have used this watch for almost 2 years now, in the ocean, in the shower, when I play soccer, hiking, you name it. I have a tan from never taking it off. Point is, maybe I've been lucky with the water, but I even use it when I go surfing, never had any problems. I'm on my third one, simply because I do so much with it that sometimes the band will get caught in some part of the boat and fall into the ocean. Thats my fault though, I use it not matter what I'm doing. Point is, I love this watch!!!!

title: Hey Casio, play Lorna Shore
text: This watch it perfection. I am an automotive technician. I wore an Apple Watch that I received as prize daily in the shop for 5 years until it finally broke. I was not going to drop the coin to replace it. Insert the classic, the original CASIO. It‚Äôs very lightweight low profile gives you date and time very clearly. Minimalist design and surprisingly tough. I have no doubt this thing will last at least a couple years. Plus if it does die it‚Äôs only $15.  I never take it off, it survives under hood duties and 10-15 heavy duty hand washing a day. I wear it in the shower and sleep in it. I like that it has a simple timer for work outs. Once I got used to not having my Apple Watch it‚Äôs honestly nice to not feel a haptic tap 50 times a day for emails and texts etc. plus it‚Äôs really funny to say ‚Äúhey Casio, call my wife‚Äù‚Ä¶.. it doesn‚Äôt‚Ä¶.. and that‚Äôs okay!

title: Great cheap, functional watch
text:
I bought one of these watches to help me keep time without having to drag out my cell phone all hours of the day. It is cheap and has basic time keeping, stopwatch, and alarm functionality. It has performed admirably for the year I've used it, even surviving a summit of Mount Kilimanjaro, where it was caked in 1/8" of ice (pics here: [...]). My only complaints are that it has no hour hand in stopwatch mode, and you can't use the backlight to view your stopwatch time, as it resets the stopwatch.

Pros:
Cheap
Easy to use
Drab appearance
Durable(water/ice/etc)

Cons:
No hours on stopwatch
Backlight button resets stopwatch
UI is somewhat un-intuitive

title: This is my Casio. There are many like it, but this one is mine.
text:
My first watch was a little blue and green affair that looked like a lily, and when you pressed a button, the lily flipped up and a little frog sprang out on a spring. Then aged 11, I got a Casio F91W and have never looked back. The strap breaks for me, on average, every three years (I wear it tight and the plastic strap gets bent 180 degrees regularly), but besides that I've never had a problem.

I thought briefly this year about getting a smart watch, but the fact is, you simply don't need a watch to do anything else than the Casio does. It tells you the time, lets you time things, and sets alarm to remind you of the time. It has one brief, and it sticks to it. And it does it forever, without complaints, without worries about it being stolen, and without ever running out of battery. I keep all my old watches, so my room is like a graveyard of Casio F91Ws, and not *one* of them has run out of battery - the only reason I'm having to get another one is because it's so cheap, it's easier to buy one than have it repaired. More money for Casio, I figure.

If you want to carry around a piece of expensive digital technology with the time on it that will regularly fail on you because you haven't charged it in 12 hours, get an iPhone. If you want a watch that tells you the time, there's an entire community of Casio buddies all over the world waiting to notice your watch and "Hey, you've got the Casio too! Aren't they cool?!" - and then say nothing else because the Casio is so Spartan, so obvious, so reliable in its simplicity the only real question you ask is "Do you have the backlight?"

Long live the Casio F91W!

title: Is it so hard to make a product out of non cancerous materials
text:
This watch made me throw out my old expensive watch collection cuz I never wore them, including my Apple Watch. This Casio is light weight and small & unlike any other so when my battery died I immediately ordered a new one but upon opening the packaging I found a notice that I must‚Äôve missed the first time. It read ‚Äúonly for California USA‚Äú I immediately knew what it meant because these days everything has a similar warning. Is a label that serves as a warning that the product one just purchased was made using cancer causing elements.
Obviously I don‚Äôt have the intention of eating my watch anytime soon however like all plastic products this will soon turn to micro-plastics and we will all be consuming it.
Americans on average are eating about 5 grams (like a credit card) worth of micro plastics a week. It‚Äôs like a little sprinkle of cancer with every meal/sip and it‚Äôs completely unnecessary. Especially in a country that shuts down the world economy for two years over a common cold with a 99.997% survival rate. Do they really care about our health or are they just profiting from our disease? I‚Äôm sending this back and from now on will be telling time only by the positioning of our celestial bodies and reading the eyes of roaming cats.

title: Affordable, but would spend more to get a better watch
text:
I bought this to replace my AE1200WH after it broke at the lug. Before that one I had an AE1000W, which is the same as the 1200WH (it just looks different). I bought this because I wanted to try a slightly cheaper watch. However, I'd go back to the AE1200WH in a heartbeat. If you have a couple extra bucks, buy an AE watch.
I wish I had known that F91-W's had push pins instead of spring pins. I intended on changing the strap for a NATO strap when I unboxed it, but it took a lot of effort to take them out without scratching the plastic. I could've just gotten an AE Casio. They have wide spring-loaded pins, which will make changing straps easier, and give you more strap options.
This watch beeps whenever you press buttons, and you can't turn it off (you can in both AE models). The built-in light doesn't really do much, while the AE models light up the whole display. AE models tell you the month. AE models also have world time, a longer stopwatch, and a timer countdown function. You can swim and take a shower with an AE and still keep your warranty. Plus, the AE1200WH looks a lot nicer than the F91-W, and I've gotten a bit of attention when I wear the AE.
Anyway, enough comparing this watch to the AE. The F91-W is still a great watch and tells me all I need to know at a moment's glance. Very useful for a kid with only a few bucks in his pocket who doesn't need a million features on his wrist.

title: for good reason. Now that I have one of my ...
text: When I ran cross country in high school, all my coaches and many of my fellow athletes wore this exact watch, for good reason. Now that I have one of my own, I can attest to its convenience and utility, especially for people who lead active lifestyles. Unlike many other sports watches, this one isn't overly bulky or heavy; whether I'm doing laps on the track or cleans in the gym, this watch isn't a hindrance to my movement in any way. The watch is also very simple: setting it up takes only a few minutes; the buttons and their respective functions are very intuitive; I personally love the stopwatch and alarm function the most, as they help me organize my workouts and my day respectively. The resin strap is also very comfortable, unlike some metal straps that are chilly and hard to the touch. The strap, being both flexible and sturdy, feels comfortable on the skin, so much so that I literally never take this watch off (because I don't have to). I'm so incredibly happy that I put in the money to buy this watch; as of this review, even though I've only had it for a few weeks, I love it to bits and will definitely recommend to others.

title: Classic, quality, and great for the price
text:
This is a wonderful watch and definitely a classic. This was one of the first of its kind and massively popular. Over time the price has decreased now it is one of the best deals there is in terms of watches.

Pros
-Price. For what you pay, this watch is just fantastic and very solid. This is a military approved watch that can take a beating, and is nice for everyday use or athletic/work use.
-Weight. This watch notably lighter than others, and this has its ups and it's downs, but it makes it nice because it is not a sinfully watch weighing on your wrist. Personally, I like big faced watches, but this is a nice change.
-Functions. On the default, there is obviously the time (with seconds), as well as the day, date, and ability to change whether it is in 12 or 24 hour format. You can toggle through to find alarm and stopwatch mode. You can set an alarm to go off at any time of the day, as well as set the hourly alarm so the watch beeps every hour on the hour. This can be a handy function when at school, work, homework, etc. when time management is important.
-Durability. Though it is no G-Shock (which I highly reccomend because they are great watches), it is nice and pretty durable as well. It is obviously water resistant, so swimming, showering, wearing in rain, etc. with this watch is no problem. Despite it's small size, it feels fairly sturdy and is fine to wear in tough conditions.
-Battery life. Though I have not come close to reaching the time for a battery change, I have learned from research as well as friends who have the watch that the battery lasts forever, which is wonderful but not exactly surprising. Since the watch is so small and simple, and it is digital, the battery on this rather than lasting the average 2-3 years, should last more like 5-10 years, which is fantastic.

Cons
-Size. The first thing I noticed upon unboxing this watch was that it was noticeably smaller than I had expected. While I knew it was not a large faced watch, the face was smaller than it appeared to me on Amazon. I have gotten used to it but this is something to note if size matters much to you.
-Strap. The strap on this watch is decent, but by no means impressive. It is pretty thin and not one of the nicest looking bands Casio makes. It does the job and seems strong enough, though over time that may change. Fortunately, that is why you can purchase replacement and different bands for it! With the right tools they are changeable; you can do this is at most watch or jewlery shops.
-Buttons. The buttons are pretty small and not always easy to press. While the locations of them is pretty standard, they are small and not always the easiest to access.
-Appearance. Though it is a classic, that does not neccesarily mean that it looks professional or very high quality. It does not look bad, especially for the average person looking for an everyday watch or a sports watch, but for someone wanting to look professional, I think it goes without saying that this may not be the watch for you.

Overall, this is a great watch and definitely worth the $9 or $10! It is a classic watch that is popular for a reason. Great buy and highly reccoment.

title: Decent watch
text:
As a watch, this is totally fine. It's affordable, it keeps good time, it has decent features and a long battery life.

The problem is the backlight... or rather, the lack of one. You see, while this watch does have a backlight, the light is positioned way up in the top left corner and barely lights the hours part of the display. You'll know it's 8-something, but don't expect to know whether it's 8:25 or 8:55.

Nevertheless, this would be a forgivable flaw if this were the best Casio could do. But that's not the case. Casio also makes the F105W-1A Illuminator, whose electroluminescent backlight illuminates the entire display with an even blue glow. Given that the F105 is roughly the same price as the F91, there's no reason to prefer the F91, except for maybe nostalgia.

2020-01-13 Update

After actually using this watch in the dark a bit, I've found that the backlight is actually adequate, so I'm bumping up my review to 5 stars. I've also noticed that the viewing angles on this watch are better than the F-105W, so there are some things that this watch does do better.

title: Great Simple Budget Watch
text: Overall this is a very good watch. I would probably be willing to pay $25, so for $10, it's an awesome deal. My first impression was that it's a little bit smaller than I was thinking. It wasn't so small that it was a problem though, and I actually came to like it later on. One problem with it being small is that it ends up slightly offset on my wrist when I have to use the hole for a larger wrist. That wasn't a huge issue though. One thing that I didn't like is that the light button also serves other functions in some modes, which can make it hard to use in the dark. That's another thing that I got used to and didn't mind later. It is definitely waterproof; it works fine for swimming, I never did try showering though. I do have to say though, don't mess with the screws. I unscrewed the back, just cause I like to look at what's inside things. I thought I got the screws all the way in, but apparently I didn't, because I went swimming later that day and broke it with getting water inside. So it's waterproof as long as you don't unscrew the back at all. So overall, it's a great watch for someone that isn't looking to spend a lot, and doesn't need a ton of functions.

text: This watch brings back so many good memories from the late 1980s. A no-frills type of wrist watch that is very light on the wrist. This version continues to showcase the faint green LED light on the left that barely iluminates the last two digits. Which in most cases are not needed to tell time in the dark. The display is sharp and easily readable from 3-4 feet away.  The water resistance feature comes in handy on rainy days. It is ok to swim with it; however, remember not to press any buttons while submerged. The wrist band is light and surprisingly well made for a sub $25 watch.  In short, this is the watch you think of wearing when mentioning a classic Casio watch.

title: After years of devices with endless features it was nice to get a simple watch to tell time and ...
text:
I bought this watch a few months ago. After years of devices with endless features it was nice to get a simple watch to tell time and to know when the hour was reached (with a satifying beep). My model, however, did not survive the water this past weekend. After a few minutes in the surf the screen came up with some default screen that had "CASio" written on it (using numbers), and then screen completely died. I have seen others write that you cannot hit buttons while wet and I am not sure if did that or not. For the $9 or $10 dollars I am going to give it another shot because I loved this thing.

The screen has come back to life, but I can't seem to set the time without the watch blinking in and out. Maybe a bit more drying off and it will work again.

The millions of buyers every year don't lie - this is the best $10 watch you can find. It's accurate, reliable, and pretty much indestructible. If you're looking for something that will be crush resistant as well, I highly recommend looking at some of the tougher Casio G-shocks.

text: Nice cheap watch. If you're planning on replacing the strap, you should know that it's a major pain in the ass to get the pins out to remove it. There are tutorials on how to do it online, but I had no luck with these pins and ended up just cutting the straps along the pin with an xacto knife to take them off. Still worked for a nylon band since the pins don't need to be out for them, but it took a bit of fiddling to squeeze the band between the watch and the pins. Also, it beeps when you press buttons and there's no way to turn that off afaik. I've gotten over it, but just FYI. Overall, I'm still happy with it.

title: Chemical Reaction
text:
The watch itself functions perfectly fine. It has an alarm, shows the days of the week, and has a light, but the light is not very powerful. Overall, it's a decent watch. (I would give it 4-5 stars if it was just fine and this was it.)

My issue with the watch is that it gave me an allergic reaction on my wrist exactly where the plastic was in contact with my skin. I think there is a toxic chemical in the plastic that I'm having a reaction to, and it's taken at least two days for my skin to actually heal.

If you look at the photo very closely, you'll see that the skin area looks like it has a lot of tiny bumps on it. (This is AFTER several days of not wearing it and letting my skin heal.) When I wear it, my skin turns red, gets a lot of bumps, and it itches.

It makes me sad to write this review because I was really looking forward to wearing this watch and enjoying it for a long time. I won't be able to unfortunately. :( I'll be looking to return it and report the issues.

title: Casio F91W-1. Practical, reliable, and affordable.
text:
The Casio F-91W Digital Sports Watch is the ideal watch for anyone that wants the ease of wearing a watch for the many functions it provides while still maintaining a high level of mobility. If you are into running, weight lifting, working outdoors, or you perform adventurous activities like hiking, this is the perfect watch for you. The very light weight and small size can almost make you forget you are wearing it during any of those activities.

This watch suits any needs that one would look for when looking for a watch with great practicality and longevity. First, it is incredibly scratch resistant. After daily use with heavy wear and tear, there are no visible scratches to note. Second, the water-resistant qualities are impressive. If you are highly forgetful like me, neglecting to remove the watch during showers or swimming, you won‚Äôt find yourself needing to buy a new watch! In terms of chronograph function, you can expect to always look down to your wrist for an accurate time, without needing frequent resets as some watches do. A stop watch with lap timer is included, which is excellent for running and other applications. An alarm setting is also present to always keep you on schedule. One of the most useful functions is that the day and date are displayed in addition to the time on the main screen. This is incredibly convenient in date keeping at work or on the go. Beyond this, maintenance is very straightforward. Battery changing is not necessary with an incredible life span, and simple functions like changing the hour during daylight savings time takes only a few total clicks to perform.

I recently purchased my second Casio F-91W Digital Sports Watch. I purchased my first during Air Force basic military training approximately 4 years ago. The watch component itself still functions on my old watch after all this time, but after about 3 and a half years of daily heavy use the resin strap broke at one of the seams. The wrist strap is replaceable as well, so you may choose to go that route. If you are a thrifty shopper, a price tag of less than $10 is definitely appealing, especially for a watch whose performance for regular, everyday use rivals that of $100 G-Shock watches that Casio also manufactures.

If you are looking for a reliable, durable, and convenient watch, this is your best bet in a watch, dollar for dollar!

title: Gains 1 second per week
text:
If you can buy such a watch for ten bucks, than an eleven dollar watch is pure indulgence.

I am deeply impressed with what Casio can do with so little. This watch is petite, nicely presented in an unassuming way, and surprisingly accurate. Your initial impression will be one of dinkiness, thin strap, semi-flat good quality black resin, with the now classical 80's retro wordy techno-babble Casio face. Lovely.

It took 3 days of carefully eyeballing time.gov before I could assert that the watch was gaining, and now I can state definitely that it is less than 1 second per week.

The only genuine weakness is the backlight. It lights from the left, so you have a fair chance of catching the hour, possibly the minute (with difficulty). Seconds, or the date, not so much. A truly darkened room helps. A movie theater is the worst case, your eyes are lit by the bright screen but the room itself is unlit. Just enjoy the movie, OK?

Petite, yes. My wife ridicules it as "a teenager's watch", and it is certainly small enough for a woman to wear. It looks like the F105W might be slightly bigger but with the same movement. In fact I spent many hours enjoyably clicking through many Casio options, and I think I'll buy some others also. There is a real pleasure of ownership here. For the price of a real watch, you could buy just about the whole catalog.

So you could get an atomic radio watch, and improve the accuracy by about half a minute a year, or 15 seconds between DST changes. You could get solar, which would extend the already-superfluous 7 year battery life. Which is not to say that I don't have the red mist for an exquisite sapphire crystal all-everything timepiece like a Citizen Blue Angels or Oceanus. But these are wrist jewelry with technology in search of a problem. I will buy one, some day. In the meantime, this Casio performs its primary function as well as a watch can.

title: A trusty companion
text:
UPDATE: after purchasing in 2018 and it now being middle of 2022 the watch is still just as great. the watch band is still intact and going strong, battery and time keeping are excellent. It is probably the watch I am most connected to. the F91 is easily forgettable on wrist. I love this little watch. I will go a few months without wearing it but unlike my mechanical watches its still "ticking" and ready to go. if the size is a concern id reccomend the w17 as its basically a modernized version (larger, better water resistance, backlight).

I've had this watch for 2 years now and have worn it off and on during this time. When I wear it it's on 24/7 in the shower and work for long periods. I've worn it on a deployment in the desert and it hasn't let me down. The backlight is ok, I personally don't think its as bad as people say. It allows you to read the time in the dark. The band has held up so far. Oh and it keeps excellent time. Many would opt to throw it out when it breaks but ill replace the battery and maybe put it on a NATO strap. Just because its cheap doesn't mean it's meant to be disposable.

title: It does its job cheaply and well.
text:
Just like the old days!

This might be the best per-dollar buy in watches. It's cheap as dirt, but it keeps time (military or civilian), serves as a stop watch, and serves as an alarm. It tells you the day and date. Settings quickly become second nature. The numbers are easy to read.

It looks pretty good, and will withstand a splash of water or a couple of seconds under a faucet. Unless you have a truly huge wrist or a truly small one, the size works. I draws little power from the battery: Casio says the battery should last ten years.

You can't go wrong. If you are a life-long nerd with a sense of history, you actually need one of these. If you want to flaunt your wealth, you need another kind of watch. This one does a few things cheaply and well.

title: Good quality for a good price!
text:
I have been using this watch for around 5 months now, in adverse and harsh conditions, and this watch is doing phenomenally well! I believe it is rated as being "water resistant", and it certainly is. I have fully submerged the watch multiple times, it is frequently exposed to running tap water, it is hit hard against steel, banged up against concrete, and it keeps perfect time and is still fully functional. It has a few good scratches on it now, but that is to be expected of any watch that is put through what I've put this one through. Outstanding little watch, especially for the price! Now, it isn't perfect. The button that switches the time display modes (switches from 1:45 to 13:45) keeps unintentionally getting pressed so that the time is displayed in the "24 hour" mode. Not a big deal, I just prefer the other mode. Also, this is not a fancy looking watch. It is very basic, and dare I say, cheap looking. Again, a minor thing.

All in all, I love this watch, I wear it every day and I'm almost lost without it. Never wore a watch before this one. I constantly check it for the time and the date. It also has a stop watch feature and an alarm. I never use either, so I am unable to comment further on those features. And it has a good sized display (I can still read it a couple of feet away without my glasses). An excellent everyday/beater watch that won't win a beauty show, but will keep on working whenever you need it to.

I recommend this watch for people with the right expectations. One of the best, simple, cheap, functional watches ever made. It came out in 91', and it looks like it. title: Casio's Contribution to Democratized Design
text: These watches are the rarest of combinations. Incredibly reliable. Shockingly low priced. And absolutely classic with the added flavor of retro-tech. Casio KNOWS they have a winner with this watch. It has sold, and continues to sell, all over the world. And yet, they keep the price low - reminding us that good design should be affordable to everyone. This is an incredibly creative and valuable contribution. For less than one hour's work, at the average minimum wage in New York State, you can afford one of these. Thank you, Casio.
