title: Once and future icon
text:
The fact that you're even looking at an online listing for this watch, which was first released approximately 30 years ago, should say all you need to know. It's simple, it wears so comfortably you'd be forgiven if you forgot it was there, and it looks timeless. Simple to use buttons, very easy to read display, and great build quality for what you pay for this watch.

There are only two downsides to this watch that affected me in my daily life, and one can be fixed if you have the technical know-how:

1. No countdown timer: this one is the only feature I truly missed in this watch having last worn more contemporary Casio digital offerings. The stopwatch works wonderfully, and the daily alarm and hourly signal get your attention, but it would be nice to be able to set a several minute or hour timer. That being said, we do live in the 21st century, so if you have a smartphone this is all moot.

2. The light: one aspect that has unfortunately remained basically unchanged since the 1990s is the illumination on this light. A barely visible green LED off to the left of the LCD panel. Running this watch stock it's difficult to read in anything other than bright light or total darkness. However, if you trust your soldering skills it's quite easy to replace this LED with an ultra bright 1206/0805 size replacement of any color you want. I've done this about a half dozen times now and it never gets old seeing this legendary watch light up like a small flashlight.

Overall would highly recommend, either as a beater watch, a first watch for a child, or a watch to practice tinkering and modding.

title: Excellent for the price
text:
I needed something cheap to tell the time while I went on a wilderness trip. This watch is slim (low profile), lightweight, cheap, and reliable. I'm not sure how water resistant it really is, but it had no trouble being submerged a little in a lake for a bit. The band is comfortable, but not breathable (obviously).

I think my complaint with this watch is the light button is not good. I really wish there was a separate button just for the light. Setting the alarm in the dark was very annoying since you can't *just* press the light button sometimes. I haven't had to use the stopwatch feature in the dark either, but I can imagine that is a big pain. The light is just pretty bad in general too. It's just a dinky LED off on one side that doesn't evenly illuminate the watch face. I think when this thing breaks, I might go for a watch with an electroluminescence (EL) light.

title: An excellent choice if you value a slim, lightweight watch
text:
The F-91W has a couple of advantages over its bigger G-Shock relatives like the DW-5600E. Its tiny case size and weight make it easy to forget you're wearing. For small to average wrists, this watch should wear just fine. It will be too small for an 8 inch wrist or larger. The 8mm thick case will easily slip under long sleeved shirts and jackets when many G-Shocks won't. It's also tough enough for probably 95% of people. I haven't managed to to break the watch and it survives lap swimming with no problems (even when its not rated for that at all.) But on the other side, the G-Shocks are rated for far better shock and water resistance and the materials quality are much better (and you'll notice immediately when you handle them.) You will get what you pay for.

The buttons are exposed on the side and that makes them extremely easy to operate. Once you memorize the layout, it's extremely easy to set a quick alarm and switch the hourly chime on/off. If you prefer 12/24 hour time in airports or train stations, you can easily switch with one button press. The alarm volume is actually pretty decent as well. It's not going to wake a really heavy sleeper, but it's louder than most G-Shock models. Test it and see if it's loud enough to wake you at home before relying on it in travel situations.

A lot of people complain about the small, weak micro LED light. I get that. But it's a compromise that keeps the case thin at 8mm. When you use the improved full-screen LED illuminator or EL backlight tech, the thickness of the watch has to increase. But the micro LED light actually does its job pretty well in actual darkness. Even if your eyes aren't adjusted to the dark, you can easily see hours and minutes with it. But if a bright light is important to you, spend a little more for the slightly bigger F-105W.

The watch's weakest aspect is the band. The resin is cheaper than a G-Shock and it lacks the curved lugs that help it wrap around the wrist. Chlorinated water from pools, sweat, and salt water will all weaken the resin over time. Over-tightening the band will stress it more too. To make the band last longer, rinse sweat and salt off the band and dry it at the end of the day, and wear it loose enough to fit one finger between the band and your wrist.

All-in-all though, the F-91W is an absolute winner if watch thinness and alarm/hourly chime are important to you. Highly recommended.

title: Cheap, Functional, Cool
text:
I've been wearing this watch for maybe 10 months now and have enjoyed it greatly - mostly because I have paid ~$7 with free shipping for a watch with all the features you need and none you don't(clutter). The band has held up, the alarm always works, the watch is easy to set, military time is included, date and week day is displayed, it can be set to beep on the hour, it has proven to be water resistant as advertised(this is no diving watch, but holds up fine to showers and washing hands, etc). Really the only thing which could be better is the watch face illumination(a single green led which illuminates the screen about 3/4 full). It's adequate for checking the time in bed or late at night outdoors, but not much else. To be honest, it's not that much of a problem, but it has to be mentioned. I would not reccomend this watch for those with a large wrist, as it will look quite small(I have a smaller than average wrist, but choose to wear it reversed facing me). I have found it to be very comfortable, as it's light weight and small size is very unobtrusive(when I take it off, I find myself looking at my wrist only to be confused when it's not there).
tl,dr: It's retro and minimalist, if that fits your bill then don't hesitate to pick one up. Why not for the price?

text: I have a Apple Watch ‚åöÔ∏è 42mm since 2017 and I get bored to put it to charge it every day although it is very good. I prefer something simple.

title: Too many reviews
text:
There are simply too many reviews of this watch. So instead of a review I‚Äôd like to share with you a conversation I had the other day with one of my co-workers.

Co-work: What‚Äôs that on your wrist? Did you borrow that watch from you 10 year old son? It‚Äôs so small and cheap looking. I didn‚Äôt think you ever knew how to read a LCD display.

Casio F-91W Owner: It‚Äôs a Casio F-91W, and no I didn‚Äôt borrow it from my son, but sometimes I let him borrow it from me. I know that I typically, prefer analogue watches with a mechanical or automatic movements. I did need to read the instruction manual I figure out how to read the digital display. Once I figured out that the colon on the display is separating the hours (on the left) from the minute (on the right) and the smaller numbers on the far right represent the seconds; it‚Äôs actual easier to read that the 3 hand analogues.

Co-work: So, why did you buy this watch? It doesn‚Äôt seem to fit in with your Seiko 5, Orient, HMT, Citizen Eco-drive or that Chinese knock-off of an expensive German watch you can‚Äôt afford, that you typically wear to the office.

Casio F-91W Owner: It‚Äôs nothing like my other watches, but this watch is one of the great classics. This model was first made in 1991, and was the smart watch of its time. The features and price-point is also unbeatable. I got it specifically because I am going on vacation to the beach and I wanted an affordable watch to wear of the beach and in the pool. This is proven technology; this model has been manufacture for over two decades and it‚Äôs almost bombproof.

Co-work: Doesn‚Äôt WR mean Water Resistant; like splash and rain resistant only. I thought you need at least a 50m or 100m rating to take it swimming.

Casio F-91W Owner: You are completely correct, and completely wrong. A watch worth worrying about needs at least a 50m or preferable a 100m rating just for swimming on the surface more or less. Personally, I wouldn‚Äôt take any of my other watches swimming on purpose, even though some of them have a 100m rating. However, this Casio is very modest in cost and I consider the manufactures water resistance rating is very under stated. Sure, if I ruin this watch swimming, the manufacture going to tell me to fly a kite, if I made a warranty claim, but this is a ten dollar watch. If you have ten dollars to wager, like I do, throw caution to the wind or perhaps dive in head first with it. It‚Äôs a lot like jaywalking, it‚Äôs not recommended, but you not trueing living your life to the fullest if you follow every rule. I sure a G-Shock with 200m water rating is manufacture with more seals and offers better water protection, but I also think that the water resistance rating is partially just marketing to separate Casio‚Äôs $10 watches from their $100 watches. I‚Äôve taken this watch in the ocean and dove in swimming pools with no problems. I‚Äôd recommend not pressing the buttons when it‚Äôs wet, as well as not being a cry baby if you ruin it, but this watch is suitable for swimming in my book.

Co-work: Wow, what a risk taker, they must be paying you too much, if you have ten bucks to risk like that. So you say it‚Äôs was the smart watch of its time back in the day. What‚Äôs so smart about this watch?

Casio F-91W Owner: Well for starters, a day-date complication with annual calendar, that only needs to be corrected for leap years. It switches between AM/PM and 24 hour format with a single push of a button. It has a hourly repeater that can be turned on and off. A stopwatch function, and am alarm. Did I mention it has a very dim light, and I believe it was y2k compliant nearly a decade in advance.

Co-work: Wow, I think my iwatch can do all that, but I don‚Äôt know how to. I also paid a lot more than you, and I can‚Äôt take it swimming. How about battery life? Where‚Äôs the charger plug? Is it self-winding, like you Seiko 5, and going to die after a few days off your wrist? I know for sure that in 1991 there was no such thing as wireless charging.

Casio F-91W Owner: It‚Äôs much for low tech then wireless charging, or self-winding. It‚Äôs powered by a replaceable battery. Casio claims 7-years on a single battery with no daily recharging required. It‚Äôs more likely that the strap will break, before the battery will need to be replaced. It doesn‚Äôt need any sunlight either, some people claim to get 10 years on a single battery, it really depends on how frequent the light and alarm functions are utilized. In theory you could hide out in a cave for years without worrying about charging or replacing the battery.

Co-work: Hey, one more question. I know you are married, but ascetically speaking, do you think I watch like this would be helpful in attraction women? It‚Äôs kind of ugly looking.

Casio F-91W Owner: Well my friend, with you ugly face and abrasive personality, if a woman takes the time to look at your watch, she‚Äôll be excited to see a practical watch on your wrist. Well unless she‚Äôs a gold digger type, but you don‚Äôt need that. Any women that can‚Äôt appreciate a classic watch like this doesn‚Äôt even desire to go dutch at McDonalds with you. However, for you, I‚Äôd strongly recommend the Casio CA53W, if you want a line of highly desirable ladies wanting to go out with you. If you wear a Casio CA53W and a lady starts a conversation about your watch, you‚Äôll need to take her somewhere nice, like a sit-down type restaurant, and pay the whole bill, and she‚Äôll surely want a second date when she see you generously calculate 18% gratuity with your calculator watch.

title: Casio forged this to survive the apocalypse
text:
Back in the dreaded years of high school, I really needed a watch for the SAT, something simple and efficient. I stumbled across this baby by looking up the highest rated digital watches on Amazon. At roughly $11 with endless stream of 5-stars, the watch seemed to be exactly what I needed. Little did I know that this Casio F91W-1 was much more than just a throwaway item. This baby has lasted through extreme usage. I hike with it; it's resistant to scratches. I swim with it; it's water-resistant. I've dropped it a few times when putting it on (I've got butter fingers) and there are no dents or scratches. You may as well nickname this the Nokia 3310 watch.

This may seem like a cheap watch, but Casio forged this thing to survive the apocalypse. If you're a fellow zombie hunter and want a sturdy, indestructible watch, this is the watch for you! All jokes aside, it is a great piece and you can't go wrong with it. Highly recommend it.

title: The Argument For Casio Watches
text: Casio is arguably the most popular name in watches ‚Äî certainly when it comes to luxury watches. Classically Japanese, since 1946 Casio has been producing watches designed for comfort, function and style. Today, Casio is one of the most powerful luxury brands in the world working hard to retain its status. Casio focuses on a few key watch lines that are quickly recognizable and highly desired the world over. Image aside, Casio watches have a reputation for being very well manufactured.

text: For someone who misses the 1980s and 1990s on a daily basis - this workhorse of a watch provides both functionality and the subtle style of a bygone fluro-wearing era. I use my hands alot, fending off attackers, saving people in burning buildings, normal stuff like that, and the faithful Casio is with me through it all. When others around you break or flee, the Casio watch stands it's ground - its the tough older brother who always has your back (wrist) when trouble comes knocking. This Casio is not for cowards.

title: what a deal...but that case/band broke :(
text:
For the price you can't beat it!! I got this because I wanted a cheap replacement for my more expensive watch, while I was trying to find a battery for it. The battery for my nike watch ended up costing about half of the price of what this watch costs total!!
My peers says this makes me look really old, but I think it's rad. It does what I need it too, and that's all that matters.

**Update
During my second year of use, while commuting on bike, my watch fell off. I found the case frame/band interface cracked and propagated enough so that a portion of the watch case broke from the rest of the frame.

My father's same watch has done the same. Unfortunately our watches broke at the frame and not the band. Therefore, we're now looking for something more robust like a g-shock. We take good care of our stuff (even if it's cheap), so this is a big downer :(

All in all, it's still a cool watch, but not worth my money (even at this price).

title: Does what others don't at the lowest price.

And it does. This watch tells time. It has an alarm. Done. Another reason i bought it was because i thought it was all plastic and could get through metal detectors at work. I failed to notice the metal backing in the product images, but for some reason, it doesn't set off the detectors regardless. So, i'm very happy with what I got for the price.

title: Nothing beats the price AND the quality!!
text:
Nothing, absolutely nothing, beats this watch in terms of quality, ruggedness AND it's price!! Been using this watch for a solid 2 years, everyday, at the college, at the gym, at the part-time job in a gas station, travel, work as a sys. admin.(server and rack installations), in the rain and under hot sun (this is India) on my motorcycle and more! Nothing can kill this gem of a watch. After numerous brushes with walls, metal etc, the only scratch on the surface is really not noticeable. The strap is excellent. No sign of wear and tear yet. The light is sufficient in any dark area.

My previous $40 from Timex lasted 1-1/2 years before the strap just rusted away with sweat. This is a great, durable, and really simple watch that keeps your time well. And at an incredible price. I got this for only $11. A thumbs up to Casio for this master piece!

title: Great Wach: Lets settle the "Water Resist" once and for all
text:
Now then, this is a fine digital watch, but there seems to be much confusion as to what the "Water Resist" term means on the face. Simply put, "How wet can I safely get my Casio F-91W?" Now then ISO standard 2281 define what makes a water resist watch.[...]
From this text I will quote section 6.2.1
"6.2.1 Resistance to air overpressure

Subject the watch to an air overpressure of 2 bar[2] and measure the flow rate of air entering the case."

Hence we can conclude that any watch bearing the marking "Water Resist", can at minimum survive at a pressure of 2bar, which in water is about 10m. Further reading in section 7.2 implies that could be closer to 20m in water, as air is more permeable. So Casio owners feel safe, you can dive to the bottom of your local pool and the F-91w should remain intact.

title: That Little Flat Black Casio Digital Watch We All Had In The Early 1980s Is Back!
text:
I needed a very basic watch for the one part of the workweek when I'm in an area without clocks, and I'm not one of those young people what carry their "cellular telephones" with them everywhere! So I looked all over the place for this <i>kind</i> of watch, which I remember being ubiquitous for years, and <i>cheap-cheap-cheap.</i> I start looking, and guess what: None of the discount stores don't carry 'em no more. But Casio still makes the original, upon which all the cheapie knockoffs are based...upon. I was looking to spend, what, $5 at most for the dollar store version. But I had no choice and ended up getting the name brand version for about $14. And it works fine, just fine. I don't need the alarm, I haven't used the light yet, I'm not in the military so I don't need the 24-hour format, but those are features that are included. I just needed it to keep accurate time, and that it does. That it does, friend. That it does.

That it does. And speaking of time, I see that my three minutes are up, and I want to thank the council for listening to me and I hope going forward we can find a solution.

title: Wear it every day - day in day out!
text: As far a watch for work and activities goes, there is no superior to the Casio F-91W. It's virtually invincible. I'm in the UK forces and I, with countless others wear this watch as it's so reliable and does everything you could want. I've swam with it, dived with it, gone neck deep in mud with it, been in below freezing temperatures for days, got oil on it, scrambled on rocks, covered in grit, in salt water for prolonged periods and yet it still goes on!! The battery life is amazing as well. All my friends agree this is the watch to have. Others have had supposed 'rugged' watches which have broken in half the time. Sure, have a fancy watch for events and going out but this watch cannot be bettered for the working day. the only reason I'm on here buying another is because I lost it after years of it putting up with me. In the 1 in million chance that it does break (or more likely, you lose it) it's only ¬£8.00 to replace. It's unbelievably good. The only thing that could be better is if you could keep the backlight on whilst changing the alarm time, which is a little annoying trying to set an alarm in the pitch black (but I just learnt the sequence of beeps after a while!).

title: Amazing...
text:
I bought a watch like this some 12 or 13 years ago (today I'm 25). I paid around 6 US dollars at that time (note sure because I live in Brazil, and I bougjt it with our currency). At that age I was complety satisfied. It usually woke me up to go to school every day. His battery lasted for amazing 7 years! I remember that its strap soon cracked, wich make me stop using it in the wrist, but the watch continued to work for many years. I still have it with me, as some kind of memory. I plain to buy a new strap and replace the battery. I sure I gonna not use it in the wrist. Although it works well, it looks like a kid/teenager watch.
So if you want a wacth to keep time, wake you up or remember any task, if you need a chronometer, if you work at dark places and want a good and cheap watch, I'm sure that this model can perfectly fullfil your needs. I you want a fancy timekeeper, buy another one.
Best regards!
Rodrigo - Brasília, Brazil

title: Reliable as always

title: Fantastic for the money!
text: I was looking for a watch to replace my USB watch that refused to recharge after a month or two. This one fit the bill perfectly! It's lightweight, tough, and won't break the bank!
